WEBVTT

00:33.650 --> 00:34.817
Thanks.

00:37.028 --> 00:39.155
Yeah, so I'll be
watching the game...

01:38.756 --> 01:39.966
What?

01:44.762 --> 01:46.347
Hi!

04:16.289 --> 04:19.375
<i>He couldn't know
that, at this very moment,</i>

04:19.458 --> 04:22.545
<i>people meeting in secret
all over the country</i>

04:22.628 --> 04:27.091
<i>were holding up their glasses
and saying in hushed voices,</i>

04:27.175 --> 04:31.846
<i>"To Harry Potter,
the boy who lived."</i>

04:38.895 --> 04:40.229
- Dan.
- Hey, man.

04:40.313 --> 04:41.647
It's great to see you.

04:41.731 --> 04:43.149
- How you doing, dude?
- How are you, mate?

04:43.232 --> 04:46.277
It's so nice to see you.
This is awesome.

04:46.360 --> 04:48.112
- This is incredible.
- Yeah, it is.

04:48.196 --> 04:50.156
Last time we were here,
you were shorter.

04:50.239 --> 04:52.200
I'm just...
just very, very slightly.

04:52.283 --> 04:54.577
That's kind of you to say.

04:54.660 --> 04:56.412
- Here we are.
- 20 years down the road.

04:56.495 --> 04:58.206
- Yeah.
- It's kind of odd.

04:58.289 --> 04:59.624
How did it come to you?
Like, I never...

04:59.707 --> 05:01.125
I would never
get to ask this question.

05:01.209 --> 05:02.460
Like, how did you end up
doing "Harry Potter"?

05:02.543 --> 05:03.544
I ended up doing it

05:03.628 --> 05:04.754
because my daughter Eleanor

05:04.837 --> 05:06.422
convinced me to read the books

05:06.505 --> 05:08.299
after I refused three times.

05:08.382 --> 05:10.259
So once "Prisoner of Azkaban"
came out, I said...

05:10.343 --> 05:11.761
Thank you, Eleanor.

05:11.844 --> 05:14.972
I said, "Okay,
I'll read these, finally."

05:15.056 --> 05:17.058
And then immediately,
I saw the movies.

05:17.141 --> 05:19.477
I just saw them.
And that hasn't happened since.

05:19.560 --> 05:23.272
Then I had to fly to Edinburgh
to meet Jo Rowling

05:23.356 --> 05:26.901
and essentially said,
"This is my vision."

05:26.984 --> 05:29.278
She said, "That's exactly
the way I see the movie."

05:29.362 --> 05:30.821
<i>When the books came out,</i>

05:30.905 --> 05:32.990
the queues of kids
around the block...

05:33.074 --> 05:36.118
I mean, thousands of them
all waiting for the latest one.

05:41.123 --> 05:42.917
So many people were beginning
to fall in love

05:43.000 --> 05:44.627
with JK Rowling's writing.

05:44.710 --> 05:47.505
I think I probably would have
been about eight years old.

05:47.588 --> 05:49.632
I think that's when
the first one came out.

05:49.715 --> 05:51.801
<i>It became, like,
our family thing.</i>

05:51.884 --> 05:53.469
My dad used to do
all the voices,

05:53.552 --> 05:56.347
<i>and my brother and I
just became obsessed.</i>

05:56.430 --> 05:58.557
We would just beg him
to keep going.

05:58.641 --> 05:59.934
And every time
he finished a chapter,

06:00.017 --> 06:01.435
we'd be like, "One more,
one more, please.

06:01.519 --> 06:02.937
"Just one more.
Please, please, please.

06:03.020 --> 06:04.146
One more, one more,
one more, one more."

06:04.230 --> 06:05.523
<i>A friend of mine at school</i>

06:05.606 --> 06:07.316
<i>had the first two.</i>

06:07.400 --> 06:09.277
And I went for a sleepover
at his house and he said,

06:09.360 --> 06:11.487
"Well, 'Philosopher's Stone'
is there on the bookshelf."

06:11.570 --> 06:14.031
<i>That's what we did
the whole sleepover.</i>

06:14.115 --> 06:15.616
<i>We just both sat there
in silence,</i>

06:15.700 --> 06:16.993
him reading
"Chamber of Secrets,"

06:17.076 --> 06:18.494
me reading
"Philosopher's Stone."

06:18.577 --> 06:19.996
And that was it, really.
I never looked back.

06:20.079 --> 06:21.664
<i>At the time of reading,</i>

06:21.747 --> 06:23.332
we instantly related
to Fred and George

06:23.416 --> 06:25.042
because there aren't
many twins in literature.

06:25.126 --> 06:26.836
<i>"The Chamber of Secrets"
was the first book</i>

06:26.919 --> 06:29.839
that I sort of genuinely
stayed up at night reading.

06:29.922 --> 06:33.968
The writing was so vivid,
the characters so relatable.

06:34.051 --> 06:39.181
It was such a intricately,
perfectly designed universe.

06:39.265 --> 06:41.350
I think it's very easy
to forget that, at the time,

06:41.434 --> 06:43.269
people were talking about,
like, the death of reading.

06:43.352 --> 06:46.022
I just think it's a beautiful
creative outlook on life,

06:46.105 --> 06:48.316
this belief
in limitless possibilities.

06:48.399 --> 06:50.985
<i>One of the many reasons
I admired JK so much</i>

06:51.068 --> 06:53.487
<i>is that millions
would now read books</i>

06:53.571 --> 06:55.740
<i>who would never have lifted
a book up in their lives.</i>

06:55.823 --> 06:59.035
And you suddenly realize
the power of writing.

06:59.118 --> 07:00.369
Hip, hip, Harry!

07:00.453 --> 07:02.079
And then in terms of casting,

07:02.163 --> 07:06.751
it was... the search
for Harry Potter was insane.

07:06.834 --> 07:09.378
The new "Harry Potter" film
are looking for children

07:09.462 --> 07:13.799
to play the three main roles in
the multi-million-pound film.

07:15.217 --> 07:17.553
I remember going to the...
the very first audition,

07:17.636 --> 07:20.806
and there was hundreds
if not thousands of people.

07:20.890 --> 07:22.141
<i>And then we realized that</i>

07:22.224 --> 07:23.601
we were the only set
of twins there

07:23.684 --> 07:25.019
who weren't wearing
identical clothing.

07:25.102 --> 07:26.896
So we ended up
going over the road

07:26.979 --> 07:30.191
and bought two identical
matching tops.

07:30.274 --> 07:31.901
- Just off the rack.
- Just off the rack.

07:31.984 --> 07:32.985
We were like,
"Right, they will do."

07:33.069 --> 07:34.570
And then off we went.

07:34.653 --> 07:37.448
They'd let us all mill,
you know, sort of congregate

07:37.531 --> 07:39.408
till they "seemingly"
walked away,

07:39.492 --> 07:41.077
and, of course, while there's
still one gentleman

07:41.160 --> 07:43.746
holding a boom mic
straight over our heads.

07:43.829 --> 07:47.917
And this little girl
asked me, "What's that?"

07:48.000 --> 07:51.170
I think I even said,
"It's a mic, duh."

07:51.253 --> 07:52.463
I was like,
"They're filming us.

07:52.546 --> 07:53.923
This is just, like, a trick."

07:54.006 --> 07:55.674
Like, as if I'd done it
before, really.

07:55.758 --> 07:57.426
And I remember it,
'cause it was Emma.

07:57.510 --> 07:59.011
I became completely gripped

07:59.095 --> 08:02.223
by the excitement
around this audition.

08:02.306 --> 08:05.601
<i>And I always knew
that I was going for Hermione</i>

08:05.684 --> 08:07.436
<i>in a way that I think
terrified my parents</i>

08:07.520 --> 08:09.146
<i>because they were like,</i>

08:09.230 --> 08:12.024
"What are we gonna do with her
if she doesn't get the part?"

08:12.108 --> 08:13.192
I was just excited.

08:13.275 --> 08:14.527
I wasn't sort of daunted.

08:14.610 --> 08:16.112
I wasn't thinking,
"I wonder how many

08:16.195 --> 08:17.530
films they're gonna make,"
anything like that.

08:17.613 --> 08:19.031
I thought,
"Oh, this will be fun."

08:19.115 --> 08:20.991
I think the biggest pressure
at the beginning

08:21.075 --> 08:22.410
was who was gonna be
Harry Potter.

08:22.493 --> 08:23.828
We couldn't find Harry.

08:23.911 --> 08:25.955
We couldn't...
we just couldn't find Harry,

08:26.038 --> 08:27.581
and it was getting
kind of weird,

08:27.665 --> 08:28.958
um, and panicky.

08:29.041 --> 08:32.544
I was in my hotel room
in London one night

08:32.628 --> 08:34.880
watching the BBC version
of "David Copperfield."

08:34.964 --> 08:36.631
<i>Immediately, a light bulb
went off in my head,</i>

08:36.715 --> 08:38.592
<i>and I said,
"This is Harry Potter."</i>

08:38.676 --> 08:41.429
<i>This is the kid we've been
looking for for months.</i>

08:41.511 --> 08:43.139
So I asked
the casting director,

08:43.222 --> 08:45.307
I said, "We've gotta get him
in here for an audition."

08:45.391 --> 08:46.976
She said,
"It's never gonna happen.

08:47.059 --> 08:49.937
"His parents do not want him
involved in this world.

08:50.020 --> 08:51.480
They don't want him
to take this role."

08:51.564 --> 08:53.315
I think the deal
was to sign on for, like,

08:53.399 --> 08:55.526
all seven films and they would
be filmed in LA.

08:55.609 --> 08:57.236
So Mum and Dad were like,
"No, that's, like,

08:57.319 --> 08:58.863
a huge disruption to his life."

08:58.946 --> 09:01.323
Fortunately, David Heyman,

09:01.407 --> 09:03.993
uh, went to the theater
a few weeks later.

09:04.076 --> 09:05.828
These two guys
in the row in front of me

09:05.911 --> 09:07.329
started sort of turning round.

09:07.413 --> 09:09.457
<i>David, being the great
producer that he is,</i>

09:09.540 --> 09:13.335
convinced Dan's father to bring
Dan in for an audition.

09:13.419 --> 09:17.298
And that's basically
when we got our Harry Potter.

09:17.381 --> 09:18.883
And action.

09:18.966 --> 09:20.676
- That's a dragon egg.
- What is it?

09:20.759 --> 09:22.511
- That's what that is.
- What is that?

09:22.595 --> 09:23.637
A dragon egg.

09:23.721 --> 09:24.805
- Uh-huh.
- Yeah.

09:24.889 --> 09:26.182
I was a very happy kid who had

09:26.265 --> 09:28.184
a really haunted quality,
apparently.

09:28.267 --> 09:30.686
"You're really sweet,
but you looked like

09:30.769 --> 09:33.022
you had real, like,
stuff going on."

09:33.105 --> 09:36.025
It was very emotional,
actually, seeing this kid

09:36.108 --> 09:37.943
sitting there talking,
and I just thought,

09:38.027 --> 09:40.029
"Yeah, that's him.
Thank God we found him."

09:40.112 --> 09:43.365
Rupert and Emma
were very easy to cast

09:43.449 --> 09:45.284
because they felt like
they jumped off the page.

09:45.367 --> 09:47.036
<i>We screen-tested
the three of them together</i>

09:47.119 --> 09:49.038
<i>to make sure that
they all had this chemistry,</i>

09:49.121 --> 09:51.707
which immediately was obvious
in the first screen test.

09:51.791 --> 09:53.667
Remember, guys,
get closer to her

09:53.751 --> 09:55.419
as she finds out
the information.

09:55.503 --> 09:57.004
And action.

09:58.214 --> 10:00.549
I never thought
to look in here.

10:00.633 --> 10:03.886
I checked this out first term
for a bit of light reading.

10:03.969 --> 10:06.555
- This is light?
- Shut up.

10:06.639 --> 10:09.350
If Filch comes around
the corner any second now,

10:09.433 --> 10:12.353
at least 50 points
off Gryffindor.

10:14.939 --> 10:18.025
I knew it! Here it is.

10:18.108 --> 10:20.569
Nicholas Flamel
is the only known

10:20.653 --> 10:23.572
maker of the Sorcerer's Stone.

10:23.656 --> 10:25.074
The what?

10:25.157 --> 10:27.743
Oh, honestly,
don't you two read?

10:27.826 --> 10:29.870
Cut. Good job.

10:30.871 --> 10:32.039
It's lovely seeing you.

10:32.122 --> 10:34.041
Yeah, this is surreal,
isn't it?

10:34.124 --> 10:36.877
How do we all feel being back
and talking about this?

10:36.961 --> 10:40.005
Well, A, really emotional,
obviously.

10:40.089 --> 10:43.050
And B, um, it feels like
no time has passed

10:43.133 --> 10:46.220
and loads of time has passed
simultaneously.

10:46.303 --> 10:47.805
Yeah, kind of much the same.
It's quite surreal.

10:47.888 --> 10:50.015
It doesn't feel like
much time has passed.

10:50.099 --> 10:52.851
It doesn't feel like we've
kind of earned a reunion yet.

10:52.935 --> 10:54.228
- Yeah.
- I know.

10:54.311 --> 10:56.355
I have had kidney stones
and a baby,

10:56.438 --> 10:57.773
so time has obviously passed.

10:57.856 --> 10:59.692
- You did mention that.
- I feel my age.

10:59.775 --> 11:02.736
But there is, like,
such a collection

11:02.820 --> 11:04.613
of, like, shared memories
and stuff

11:04.697 --> 11:06.115
that we just all did together
that it is

11:06.198 --> 11:07.783
immediately
very easy to be, like...

11:07.866 --> 11:09.451
to sort of slip back
into where you were.

11:09.535 --> 11:11.996
Our first audition, the...
the day we all met...

11:12.079 --> 11:13.873
- Oh, my God, yeah.
- I think for the first time,

11:13.956 --> 11:15.624
there was, like, me walking
out of my dressing room

11:15.708 --> 11:17.585
and seeing, like,
another, like,

11:17.668 --> 11:19.461
young, brown-haired boy
going the other way.

11:19.545 --> 11:20.838
I never saw his face,
but I was like,

11:20.921 --> 11:22.131
"You are clearly another Harry

11:22.214 --> 11:23.632
that is being
tested out today."

11:23.716 --> 11:25.217
- And they were, like...
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

11:25.301 --> 11:26.802
Testing us with various
different configurations

11:26.885 --> 11:27.886
of Ron, Harry, and Hermione.

11:27.970 --> 11:29.305
I remember there was one

11:29.388 --> 11:31.098
where they put all
the three of us together.

11:31.181 --> 11:33.934
I do remember that
when it was the three of us,

11:34.018 --> 11:36.770
- something felt different...
- Right. Yeah.

11:36.854 --> 11:39.481
And, like, right and easy.
I do remember the click.

11:39.565 --> 11:41.275
<i>We'd been out
at the studios.</i>

11:41.358 --> 11:43.694
They'd told us we got the parts
and they were like, "Cool.

11:43.777 --> 11:45.529
"So we're announcing
you've got the parts.

11:45.613 --> 11:48.324
There is now going to be a lot
of media outside your house."

11:48.407 --> 11:49.575
So you can't go home."

11:49.658 --> 11:51.035
So far, it's sort of

11:51.118 --> 11:53.912
turned things upside down.

11:53.996 --> 11:56.332
Um, it's... I don't know,

11:56.415 --> 11:59.126
I've never had anything
happen to me like this before.

11:59.209 --> 12:02.171
Hermione made
complete sense to me.

12:02.254 --> 12:03.797
<i>That's me.</i>

12:03.881 --> 12:05.507
<i>Like, I am that girl.</i>

12:05.591 --> 12:09.511
Well, Emma was arguably
the smartest person on the set,

12:09.595 --> 12:11.096
and I'm talking
about everybody.

12:11.180 --> 12:13.557
She just was...
she was a brilliant kid.

12:13.641 --> 12:16.060
I think I'm scarily
like my character.

12:17.978 --> 12:20.856
'Cause I live in a family
of, um, seven

12:20.939 --> 12:23.067
and, um, I've got
a redheaded sister

12:23.150 --> 12:24.443
and I live in a burrow.

12:24.526 --> 12:26.945
Rupert is just the most
camera-ready

12:27.029 --> 12:29.531
12-year-old boy in the world
at that point.

12:29.615 --> 12:34.078
Like, he was so,
like, just fearless.

12:34.161 --> 12:37.206
Rupert was Ron, you know,

12:37.289 --> 12:39.625
and Dan kind of was Harry.

12:39.708 --> 12:41.877
How do you feel
about becoming famous?

12:41.960 --> 12:44.296
It'd be cool.

12:44.380 --> 12:45.798
We were all talking about this,

12:45.881 --> 12:48.384
how comfortable you made us all
in our auditions

12:48.467 --> 12:49.635
and how, like, this, like,

12:49.718 --> 12:51.762
extended massively
into the set.

12:51.845 --> 12:54.556
My memory of it is that
it seemed effortless to you.

12:54.640 --> 12:57.851
Well, on the first film,
I was dying the entire time,

12:57.935 --> 12:59.728
but I just... I always believe

12:59.812 --> 13:01.605
you cannot bring
that kind of anxiety.

13:01.689 --> 13:03.440
I want everyone
to feel comfortable.

13:03.524 --> 13:05.150
I want everyone
to feel like it's a family.

13:05.234 --> 13:07.069
I want everyone
to feel like they're home.

13:28.382 --> 13:29.883
Hey, class, listen to me.

13:29.967 --> 13:31.468
Welcome to your first
flying lesson.

13:31.552 --> 13:34.096
I want you to raise your hand
over the broom.

13:34.179 --> 13:36.056
For the first several weeks
on the film,

13:36.140 --> 13:39.727
the kids
are basically in shock.

13:39.810 --> 13:42.438
<i>Looking back, I am sort
of amazed at the fact</i>

13:42.521 --> 13:44.648
<i>that I wasn't ever, like,
completely overwhelmed by it.</i>

13:44.732 --> 13:46.734
- Shh. Shh. Shh.
- Dan, when you turn away

13:46.817 --> 13:48.944
from her this time...
when you turn away,

13:49.027 --> 13:50.446
grab hold of this,

13:50.529 --> 13:52.573
and look up like you're
going to get it, okay?

13:52.656 --> 13:54.616
<i>But I also think
that was, again, part of Chris</i>

13:54.700 --> 13:56.076
and the whole crew just, like,

13:56.160 --> 13:57.703
they kept us having fun
the whole time.

13:57.786 --> 13:59.788
Obviously, we were just kids,
and we were all

13:59.872 --> 14:01.874
looking forward
to mucking about together.

14:01.957 --> 14:04.001
<i>Chris Columbus
made the atmosphere</i>

14:04.084 --> 14:05.669
<i>very much like a funfair.</i>

14:05.753 --> 14:09.089
We were very much just, like,
kids being kids on a set.

14:09.173 --> 14:10.591
- Mm-hmm.
- My residing memory

14:10.674 --> 14:13.010
from the first...
from "Philosopher's Stone"

14:13.093 --> 14:14.803
is I just learned
how to play slam.

14:14.887 --> 14:17.222
You know what we did a lot of
as well was that game.

14:17.306 --> 14:18.515
- Oh, my God.
- Slaps.

14:18.599 --> 14:19.975
- So much hand slaps.
- Oh, slaps.

14:20.058 --> 14:21.393
With, like, all of us,
like, red...

14:21.477 --> 14:23.145
like, red, raw hands
from, like,

14:23.228 --> 14:24.646
- hitting each other really hard.
- I think we also upgraded

14:24.730 --> 14:26.815
- to knuckles as well.
- Oh, and shins.

14:26.899 --> 14:28.233
- Yeah.
- I remember the shin version.

14:28.317 --> 14:30.068
- Mm-hmm.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

14:31.195 --> 14:33.822
Sorry. Gotta give it back.

14:33.906 --> 14:36.533
I am the champion!

14:36.617 --> 14:39.161
They probably made their jobs
harder for themselves

14:39.244 --> 14:40.996
by letting us have
as much fun as we had

14:41.079 --> 14:42.623
because it distracted us from,

14:42.706 --> 14:44.249
you know, the work
we were supposed to be doing.

14:44.333 --> 14:47.085
And for the other viewers,
get a mousetrap.

14:47.169 --> 14:48.545
Darling, don't put it
on your nose.

14:48.629 --> 14:49.922
You're gonna remove
all your makeup.

14:50.005 --> 14:51.632
Like, a big problem
was, like,

14:51.715 --> 14:54.843
throughout a take,
our attention would, like...

14:54.927 --> 14:57.054
would wane and come and go.

14:57.137 --> 14:59.014
<i>They'd say a line and then
they'd smile at the camera</i>

14:59.097 --> 15:01.683
where they were just so happy
to be in a Harry Potter film

15:01.767 --> 15:04.228
<i>that they couldn't contain
their excitement long enough</i>

15:04.311 --> 15:06.188
<i>to focus on an entire scene.</i>

15:06.271 --> 15:07.773
Guys, guys, guys, guys.

15:07.856 --> 15:10.734
Columbus had worked
with kids a lot.

15:10.818 --> 15:12.778
And he was terrific with them.
He really was.

15:12.861 --> 15:15.364
He used to go down on his knees
to talk to them

15:15.447 --> 15:17.866
and huddle around
so nobody could hear.

15:17.950 --> 15:19.409
He was such a dad as well.

15:19.493 --> 15:20.953
Like, and I... you could
really feel that,

15:21.036 --> 15:23.705
like you were kind of
part of his family.

15:23.789 --> 15:26.041
Be a little looser with this.

15:26.124 --> 15:28.126
And just be talking,
you know what I'm saying?

15:28.210 --> 15:29.419
- Yeah.
- You go up and you're, like,

15:29.503 --> 15:31.255
frozen like this,
but you can be...

15:31.338 --> 15:32.673
"You really think"...

15:32.756 --> 15:34.758
"Of course I can use it,"
like this, okay?

15:34.842 --> 15:36.552
- Yeah.
- Good job, though.

15:36.635 --> 15:38.220
But it's not easy,
'cause it takes a tremendous

15:38.303 --> 15:40.389
amount of patience with kids,

15:40.472 --> 15:43.475
particularly with...
with kids as hyperactive

15:43.559 --> 15:44.893
and as excitable
as we all were.

15:47.229 --> 15:48.814
- Looking great.
- Well, they wanted to...

15:48.897 --> 15:50.315
Fancy seeing you boys here.

15:50.399 --> 15:52.943
- Hi.
- Snuck away.

15:53.026 --> 15:54.695
A couple of Gryffindors
just kicking it.

15:54.778 --> 15:56.572
- Come here.
- Good to see you, brother.

15:57.698 --> 16:00.868
How did Chris Columbus stay
is such good... good spirits?

16:00.951 --> 16:02.911
We sort of ran around.
I guess we were all, like, 11.

16:02.995 --> 16:05.205
You might get, like, three
people to do the right thing.

16:05.289 --> 16:06.665
But it doesn't mean you're
gonna get the other five

16:06.748 --> 16:08.125
in the background
doing the right thing.

16:08.208 --> 16:09.626
No. No. And Rupert
was... was relentless.

16:09.710 --> 16:11.253
Once he started...
once the flood gate open...

16:11.336 --> 16:13.005
- God, yeah.
- But that's the thing.

16:13.088 --> 16:14.590
That's the way it worked,
wasn't it?

16:14.673 --> 16:15.924
'Cause Columbus basically just

16:16.008 --> 16:17.426
- let us be kids.
- Yeah. True.

16:17.509 --> 16:19.303
I never recall feeling
like we were working.

16:19.386 --> 16:20.929
But that's so important,
isn't it, that we had that...

16:21.013 --> 16:22.431
Yeah. I think that's why
it feels that way

16:22.514 --> 16:23.724
when you watch it.
It feels like...

16:23.807 --> 16:25.267
- Yeah. That's true.
- Kids.

16:25.350 --> 16:26.602
I tell you what's funny
about that, though, is...

16:26.685 --> 16:28.270
is being surrounded
by all the...

16:28.353 --> 16:30.647
the cream of the, um,
the British acting industry

16:30.731 --> 16:32.733
and not having a clue
who anyone is.

16:32.816 --> 16:34.651
I thought... I thought
Richard Harris worked here

16:34.735 --> 16:36.820
as like... as a tour guide
for a while.

16:40.657 --> 16:43.577
<i>I don't think any of
the kids had the capability</i>

16:43.660 --> 16:45.329
of understanding the gravity

16:45.412 --> 16:47.247
of who they were
dealing with at the time.

16:47.331 --> 16:49.875
That was no stranger
Hagrid met in the village.

16:49.958 --> 16:51.627
It was Snape, which means

16:51.710 --> 16:53.670
he knows how to get past
Fluffy.

16:53.754 --> 16:55.172
And with Dumbledore gone...

16:55.255 --> 16:56.673
Good afternoon.

16:56.757 --> 16:59.301
<i>The British royalty
of the acting world.</i>

16:59.384 --> 17:00.886
<i>What have you got to say
for yourself?</i>

17:00.969 --> 17:02.554
<i>I swear I don't know
how it happened!</i>

17:02.638 --> 17:04.932
<i>When I think of the people
that I got to</i>

17:05.015 --> 17:08.268
just grow up around
and hear... hear them interact

17:08.352 --> 17:10.854
and hear the quickness
of people.

17:10.938 --> 17:13.397
<i>The adult actors came in</i>

17:13.482 --> 17:15.483
and were, like, the mischief
in a funny way.

17:18.111 --> 17:19.279
That's actually great.

17:19.363 --> 17:20.821
Like Robbie Coltrane.

17:20.906 --> 17:21.949
He was such a kid.

17:22.031 --> 17:23.825
Like, so immature

17:23.909 --> 17:27.329
and, like, just so much fun.

17:27.412 --> 17:28.580
He loved making us laugh,

17:28.664 --> 17:30.457
and he was
incredibly good at it.

17:30.540 --> 17:32.709
I've tried
absolutely everything.

17:32.793 --> 17:35.379
I've tried creams.
I've tried jellies.

17:35.462 --> 17:36.838
I tried shaving.

17:36.922 --> 17:38.715
Every moment...
I woke up, it's like...

17:38.799 --> 17:40.968
my husband is threatening
to leave me.

17:41.051 --> 17:42.511
If he really loved me,

17:42.594 --> 17:44.888
he wouldn't mind a little
facial hair, I'm sure.

17:44.972 --> 17:47.349
But he's being very,
very difficult.

17:50.394 --> 17:52.854
That, like, kindness
and that warmth from you...

17:52.938 --> 17:55.190
- Aww.
- It made all the difference.

17:55.273 --> 17:57.025
Well, we spent
so much time together.

17:57.109 --> 17:59.236
I know. I know.
I spent more time with you

17:59.319 --> 18:01.029
than I did with my own
children at one point.

18:01.113 --> 18:02.114
I know. Wild.

18:02.197 --> 18:03.740
Ooh. I know.

18:03.824 --> 18:05.575
I think most of my
favorite scenes, if I'm honest,

18:05.659 --> 18:08.996
looking back, are with you
and the gang in Hagrid's hut.

18:09.079 --> 18:10.956
I keep thinking
about that scene

18:11.039 --> 18:12.541
- where I get called a mudblood.
- Yes.

18:12.624 --> 18:14.835
And you were so sweet
with me that day.

18:14.918 --> 18:17.045
'Cause it was, like, my first,
like, you know,

18:17.129 --> 18:18.463
big piece of acting.

18:23.093 --> 18:24.428
He called me a mudblood.

18:24.511 --> 18:26.888
He did not.

18:26.972 --> 18:28.223
What's a mudblood?

18:28.306 --> 18:30.142
It means dirty blood.

18:30.225 --> 18:33.061
Mudblood's a really foul name
for someone who is Muggle-born.

18:33.145 --> 18:36.481
Someone with non-magic parents.
Someone like me.

18:36.565 --> 18:38.692
The three of you have become
such great actors.

18:38.775 --> 18:40.110
Being on that set,

18:40.193 --> 18:42.279
you felt like you actually
entered the world.

18:42.362 --> 18:43.530
Yeah.

18:43.613 --> 18:45.032
With all of Stuart Craig's
sets,

18:45.115 --> 18:46.533
the attention to detail
was phenomenal.

18:51.329 --> 18:54.583
I was always adamant
that Hogwarts shouldn't feel

18:54.666 --> 18:58.837
as if it's a world
that couldn't exist in reality.

18:58.920 --> 19:01.089
<i>I had a tremendous amount
of creative freedom,</i>

19:01.173 --> 19:04.426
<i>so we could build this world
from the ground up.</i>

19:04.509 --> 19:07.304
<i>Some of the sets on "Potter"
were overwhelming to me,</i>

19:07.387 --> 19:08.889
<i>and I'd been doing it
for 35 years.</i>

19:08.972 --> 19:10.265
You know? "Oh, blimey."

19:10.348 --> 19:12.934
The very first time
I visited the set,

19:13.018 --> 19:14.811
they walked me through
the Great Hall,

19:14.895 --> 19:18.106
which was mind-blowing.

19:18.190 --> 19:20.609
<i>All the floors
are real Yorkstone.</i>

19:20.692 --> 19:22.778
<i>A lot of those scenes
with 250 extras,</i>

19:22.861 --> 19:24.654
<i>they're all about 18
and trampling 'round.</i>

19:24.738 --> 19:26.364
<i>You're not gonna put
a plastic floor down.</i>

19:26.448 --> 19:28.158
<i>It's gotta be the real stuff.</i>

19:28.241 --> 19:30.786
<i>And all these lit candles
going up and down on wires.</i>

19:30.869 --> 19:32.496
<i>One of my favorite
moments on set ever</i>

19:32.579 --> 19:34.122
<i>was the moment
when all the floating candles</i>

19:34.206 --> 19:35.832
started burning through
the ropes that tied them

19:35.916 --> 19:37.459
to the ceiling
and just started falling

19:37.542 --> 19:39.795
- around the Great Hall.
- Hundreds of real candles

19:39.878 --> 19:41.588
- that were really lit...
- "Oh, my God."

19:41.671 --> 19:44.633
On fishing line
from the ceiling.

19:44.716 --> 19:46.468
So much of that would
be visual effects now.

19:46.551 --> 19:48.053
The fact that we got
to actually be on that set...

19:48.136 --> 19:49.805
Actually, that's so true.
That's so cool.

19:49.888 --> 19:51.348
- Thank you, Stuart Craig.
- Yeah.

19:51.431 --> 19:52.974
- Yeah.
- We love you, Stuart Craig.

20:03.318 --> 20:05.237
<i>The hardest scene to shoot
was Quidditch.</i>

20:05.320 --> 20:06.488
And the audience had to

20:06.571 --> 20:07.989
understand the rules
immediately.

20:08.073 --> 20:10.534
Quidditch is easy enough
to understand.

20:10.617 --> 20:14.162
Each team has seven players:
three chasers, two beaters,

20:14.246 --> 20:16.832
one keeper,
and the seeker... that's you.

20:16.915 --> 20:20.210
So Jo Rowling basically did
a rule book for us.

20:20.293 --> 20:21.586
A Quidditch rule book

20:21.670 --> 20:24.840
explaining every detail
of the game.

20:24.923 --> 20:26.800
<i>Then, with Stuart Craig,
our production designer,</i>

20:26.883 --> 20:29.010
<i>designed the look
of the Quidditch pitch</i>

20:29.094 --> 20:34.015
<i>and really create a pitch
that felt authentic and real</i>

20:34.099 --> 20:37.018
<i>for a game
that is completely unreal.</i>

20:37.102 --> 20:40.021
Lots of energy, enthusiasm.

20:40.105 --> 20:41.523
Set and action!

20:41.606 --> 20:44.484
- She scores!
- Angelina Johnson scores!

20:44.568 --> 20:46.278
Ten points for Gryffindor.

20:46.361 --> 20:47.529
I always wanted
to tell you this,

20:47.612 --> 20:48.947
but there was a moment,
you know,

20:49.030 --> 20:50.323
on day two maybe or three,

20:50.407 --> 20:53.034
the camera pushes into you
and you say,

20:53.118 --> 20:54.578
"We're not going home,
not really."

20:54.661 --> 20:58.165
Feels strange to be
going home, doesn't it?

20:58.248 --> 21:00.417
I'm not going home.

21:00.500 --> 21:02.335
Not really.

21:02.419 --> 21:04.004
I got tears...
I still get tears in my eyes

21:04.087 --> 21:06.381
thinking about it.
I thought, "This guy...

21:06.464 --> 21:08.383
this kid is an amazing actor."

21:08.466 --> 21:10.635
- Oh, that's...
- And it was that moment

21:10.719 --> 21:12.846
that kind of opened up
the whole world for us.

21:12.929 --> 21:15.599
And the first film was very
storybook, very inviting.

21:15.682 --> 21:16.892
Yeah, it's lovely and...

21:16.975 --> 21:18.268
It's like,
"Welcome to Hogwarts."

21:18.351 --> 21:19.728
Until you get to the end
of the movie.

21:19.811 --> 21:21.354
And where a man...
I melt a man's face.

21:21.438 --> 21:22.731
Yes, exactly.

21:26.902 --> 21:29.654
- The first film was a hit.
- Yep.

21:29.738 --> 21:32.282
So once it became a hit
and people accepted

21:32.365 --> 21:33.575
not only the film

21:33.658 --> 21:35.076
- but accepted the cast...
- Right, yeah.

21:35.160 --> 21:36.703
I had a ball
on the second film,

21:36.786 --> 21:39.206
"The Chamber of Secrets,"
'cause I was, like, free.

22:03.146 --> 22:06.191
Okay, come on. Shh, shh.

22:06.274 --> 22:07.817
Okay, come on.

22:09.361 --> 22:10.403
Shh, come on.

22:12.197 --> 22:14.115
Morning, Weasleys.

22:14.199 --> 22:15.784
Morning, Dad.

22:15.867 --> 22:19.079
I always loved any scene
where the kind of Weasleys

22:19.162 --> 22:20.622
were together,
like the Burrow scenes.

22:20.705 --> 22:22.290
<i>It just had
this frenetic energy.</i>

22:22.374 --> 22:25.126
<i>Everyone kind of played
off each other.</i>

22:25.210 --> 22:27.128
The thing about the Burrow
as I remember is that

22:27.212 --> 22:28.421
it changed all the time.

22:28.505 --> 22:30.090
It sort of expanded
and contracted.

22:30.173 --> 22:32.926
One minute, there was a huge
fireplace of floo powder

22:33.009 --> 22:36.221
and then there was just...
and then it got smaller.

22:36.304 --> 22:39.015
Yeah, it was like a living,
breathing set that changed.

22:39.099 --> 22:40.350
I feel like being a Weasley

22:40.433 --> 22:41.935
is the best part
of being in Harry Potter.

22:42.018 --> 22:44.354
We had, like, our Hogwarts
family but I felt, like,

22:44.437 --> 22:46.940
so special having
an actual extra family.

22:47.023 --> 22:48.525
- It was great.
- All these scenes that we got

22:48.608 --> 22:49.818
on top of everything else.

22:49.901 --> 22:51.611
Julie's brilliant
to work with.

22:51.695 --> 22:54.948
We used to... Ron would say,
"Hello, Mummy. Hello, Daddy."

22:55.031 --> 22:57.575
Julie Walters who played
my mother, Mrs. Weasley,

22:57.659 --> 23:00.453
was... was just so wonderful
and brilliant to me.

23:00.537 --> 23:02.497
<i>She really kind of took me
under her wing</i>

23:02.580 --> 23:04.874
and she just was, like,
the perfect mother figure.

23:04.958 --> 23:07.502
<i>The twins were two people
that I was really close with.</i>

23:07.585 --> 23:09.504
They really were like
older brothers.

23:09.587 --> 23:11.673
<i>Julie Walters
and Mark Williams,</i>

23:11.756 --> 23:13.383
<i>they were like
my second family.</i>

23:13.466 --> 23:14.884
They were always kind of
staying in character

23:14.968 --> 23:16.678
and they would have
this kind of...

23:16.761 --> 23:18.221
they would
bounce off each other.

23:18.305 --> 23:20.390
Dumbled... dom... mith.

23:20.473 --> 23:22.183
Who? Who, dear?

23:22.267 --> 23:24.185
Dumbledore must know
you're here, Harry.

23:25.770 --> 23:27.063
Cut.

23:27.147 --> 23:28.773
Stop, stop.

23:28.857 --> 23:30.525
This isn't working.

23:30.608 --> 23:31.693
Can't believe it.

23:31.776 --> 23:33.236
- You guys look great.
- Hello.

23:33.320 --> 23:34.779
How are you?
This is amazing.

23:34.863 --> 23:36.031
- How're you guys doing?
- Very well, thank you.

23:36.114 --> 23:37.490
- How are you?
- Good.

23:37.574 --> 23:39.200
- This is so exciting.
- Yeah.

23:39.284 --> 23:40.618
It's the first time
I've been back since "Azkaban."

23:40.702 --> 23:42.370
We didn't know
you were gonna come back.

23:42.454 --> 23:46.207
<i>The Weasley family values
were consideration,</i>

23:46.291 --> 23:48.835
thoughtfulness, and fun!

23:48.918 --> 23:52.339
Now, Harry, you must know
all about Muggles.

23:52.422 --> 23:56.051
Tell me, what exactly is
the function of a rubber duck?

23:56.134 --> 23:58.678
<i>It's just very natural
when we were all together.</i>

23:58.762 --> 24:01.848
It was a family,
you know, in all but name.

24:01.931 --> 24:03.475
That's the cool thing about
it as well is that you see

24:03.558 --> 24:06.519
that... that motion
where they are very inclusive

24:06.603 --> 24:09.731
and then you see the complete
opposite with the Malfoys.

24:09.814 --> 24:11.816
Yeah, it's always such
a good comparison,

24:11.900 --> 24:13.151
the two families side by side.

24:13.234 --> 24:14.903
A real chalk and cheese
side of it.

24:14.986 --> 24:17.739
Not now, Draco. Play nicely.

24:19.449 --> 24:22.077
Mr. Potter.

24:22.160 --> 24:24.621
Lucius Malfoy.

24:24.704 --> 24:26.373
We meet at last.

24:26.456 --> 24:27.874
I was first aware
of Harry Potter

24:27.957 --> 24:29.417
because everybody
was reading the books

24:29.501 --> 24:31.336
on the tube everywhere I went.

24:31.419 --> 24:33.088
<i>I'm convinced I ended up
playing Lucius</i>

24:33.171 --> 24:34.672
<i>because I didn't want to.</i>

24:34.756 --> 24:36.299
<i>I went to audition
for Gilderoy Lockhart</i>

24:36.383 --> 24:37.926
<i>and Chris said,
"That was great.</i>

24:38.009 --> 24:39.594
<i>Would you mind reading
a different part?"</i>

24:39.677 --> 24:41.805
I was about to play
Captain Hook in "Peter Pan"

24:41.888 --> 24:43.098
and I thought,
"Well, I don't wanna play

24:43.181 --> 24:44.599
two children's villains."

24:44.682 --> 24:47.227
<i>And I read
through gritted teeth.</i>

24:47.310 --> 24:48.770
<i>I was deeply bitter,</i>

24:48.853 --> 24:51.064
and, of course, that's exactly
what was necessary,

24:51.147 --> 24:54.442
and they asked me to play
Lucius, and thank God they did.

24:54.526 --> 24:56.444
How dare you?

24:56.528 --> 24:58.655
<i>The point of him
being in the story to me</i>

24:58.738 --> 25:01.700
was to explain why Draco
was such a horrible,

25:01.783 --> 25:04.911
<i>heartless,
sadistic bully at school.</i>

25:04.994 --> 25:07.831
Red hair
and a hand-me-down robe?

25:07.914 --> 25:10.083
You must be a Weasley.

25:10.166 --> 25:12.210
He's a product
of his parents, Draco,

25:12.293 --> 25:15.296
<i>and he's got
really bad parents.</i>

25:15.380 --> 25:17.090
If Hagrid
was your first influence,

25:17.173 --> 25:18.466
chances are, you're gonna be...

25:18.550 --> 25:19.968
"All right there, mate."

25:20.051 --> 25:21.511
You're gonna be lovely
and... and very huggy.

25:21.594 --> 25:24.180
Isn't he beautiful?
Oh, bless him.

25:24.264 --> 25:27.600
Look, he knows his mummy.

25:27.684 --> 25:29.477
Ooh!

25:30.562 --> 25:32.147
If your dad is a psychopath

25:32.230 --> 25:34.691
wielding a cobra cane about,

25:34.774 --> 25:36.985
you're probably not gonna be
the friendliest geezer.

25:37.068 --> 25:39.362
37, take one.
Camera mark.

25:39.446 --> 25:43.533
Tom, remember, slow.
You're telling a tale.

25:43.616 --> 25:47.162
But sinister, soft.
Set and action.

25:47.245 --> 25:49.497
<i>I adored Tom
from the second I met him.</i>

25:49.581 --> 25:52.459
He was always just
the biggest sweetheart.

25:52.542 --> 25:55.170
Working with Jason
was a real treat.

25:56.254 --> 25:58.715
In fact, working with Jason
was not always a treat.

25:58.798 --> 26:03.219
Just immediately turned
into the most unfriendly,

26:03.303 --> 26:05.430
horrible person I've ever met.

26:05.513 --> 26:08.224
<i>I just remember grabbing him
and... and just being</i>

26:08.308 --> 26:10.059
<i>as unpleasant
as I possibly could</i>

26:10.143 --> 26:13.021
and watching his little face
constantly seeking my approval.

26:13.104 --> 26:15.773
The very first scene
that I shot was actually cut

26:15.857 --> 26:17.358
and is on the deleted scenes.

26:17.442 --> 26:19.652
<i>Draco touched something,
and I used this cane</i>

26:19.736 --> 26:20.820
<i>and I went...</i>

26:20.904 --> 26:23.364
Don't touch anything, Draco.

26:23.448 --> 26:25.492
But I didn't know
how sharp the teeth were

26:25.575 --> 26:27.619
and they went right
into little Tom's hands

26:27.702 --> 26:31.039
and he looked up at me
and his eyes welled with tears.

26:31.122 --> 26:32.540
Yes, Father.

26:32.624 --> 26:34.459
And I went, "Tom, I'm so
sorry, I didn't realize

26:34.542 --> 26:36.252
how sharp they were
and how heavy it was."

26:36.336 --> 26:37.879
And he went,
"No, no, it's all right.

26:37.962 --> 26:39.005
It was good for the scene."

26:39.088 --> 26:40.548
He'd be this evil father,

26:40.632 --> 26:42.091
<i>and then they'd say, "Cut."</i>

26:42.175 --> 26:43.718
And he'll come and give you
a cuddle and say,

26:43.801 --> 26:45.553
"Oh, did I hit you too hard?
Did I hit you too hard?"

26:45.637 --> 26:48.556
He's a real, you know,
Jekyll and Hyde, that one.

26:51.100 --> 26:53.686
Yeah! Yeah!

26:53.770 --> 26:56.606
Whoo-hoo! Yeah!

26:56.689 --> 26:58.816
Harry Potter.

26:58.900 --> 27:00.610
Such an honor it is.

27:00.693 --> 27:02.403
I remember saying
to a friend,

27:02.487 --> 27:06.157
"You know, I've got this part.
It's an elf in Harry Potter."

27:06.241 --> 27:11.996
And the squeals of joy
and the complete despair

27:12.080 --> 27:15.166
at my not understanding,
you know,

27:15.250 --> 27:17.502
how important
this character was.

27:20.838 --> 27:22.423
We did a take and he goes,

27:22.507 --> 27:24.384
"Thank you, this will be all,"
and I swung my leg out,

27:24.467 --> 27:26.427
and I stepped down
and I swung my stick,

27:26.511 --> 27:28.012
and Chris goes, "Cut.

27:28.096 --> 27:29.931
Can we clean the floor
where Jason slipped, please?"

27:30.014 --> 27:31.683
And I said,
"No, I didn't slip."

27:31.766 --> 27:33.268
He said, "Well, what happened?"

27:33.351 --> 27:35.687
And I said, "I kicked Dobby
down the stairs."

27:42.110 --> 27:44.028
And I just thought,
"This is gonna be

27:44.112 --> 27:46.364
ridiculously good fun."

27:46.447 --> 27:48.783
Mr. Malfoy.

27:48.866 --> 27:51.369
Mr. Malfoy!

27:51.452 --> 27:53.913
I have something of yours.

27:55.039 --> 27:57.500
The sock is pathetic,
isn't it, on one level?

27:57.584 --> 27:59.669
<i>But on another level,
it's everything,</i>

27:59.752 --> 28:03.131
<i>and that's, I think,
the beauty of the character.</i>

28:03.214 --> 28:06.509
Master has given Dobby
a sock?

28:06.593 --> 28:08.678
What? I didn't g...

28:08.761 --> 28:12.807
Master has presented Dobby
with clothes.

28:12.890 --> 28:15.810
Dobby is free.

28:15.893 --> 28:17.854
One of the major themes
is this alliance

28:17.937 --> 28:20.356
of friends who endure.

28:34.662 --> 28:37.665
So you and I had one of
our greatest laughs together...

28:37.749 --> 28:39.208
- Yes.
- With Richard Harris.

28:39.292 --> 28:42.253
<i>And we had
a animatronic version</i>

28:42.337 --> 28:43.588
<i>of Fawkes the phoenix</i>

28:43.671 --> 28:45.381
and it was this bird...
big, red bird

28:45.465 --> 28:46.841
- that doesn't exist in life.
- That does not exist.

28:46.924 --> 28:48.551
It's not...
it wasn't unrealistic.

28:48.635 --> 28:50.219
Like, it could, I guess.

28:50.303 --> 28:53.890
<i>Richard came in and looked
at the phoenix and said,</i>

28:53.973 --> 28:57.018
"Wow, they train these animals
marvelously these days."

28:57.101 --> 28:58.811
<i>'Cause they had a camera
inside the eyes,</i>

28:58.895 --> 29:00.688
<i>so they could see
Richard looking at it,</i>

29:00.772 --> 29:02.106
<i>and then they were like,</i>

29:02.190 --> 29:04.484
<i>"Well, we don't wanna
break the spell,</i>

29:04.567 --> 29:06.319
so we'll just keep the bird
reacting and moving."

29:06.402 --> 29:08.279
And then that, of course,
you know, got into a cycle

29:08.363 --> 29:10.365
where Richard was like,
"The bird is responding to me."

29:10.448 --> 29:14.577
Ah, fascinating creatures,
phoenixes.

29:14.661 --> 29:18.039
They can carry
immensely heavy loads,

29:18.122 --> 29:21.501
and their... their tears
have healing powers.

29:21.584 --> 29:23.044
- We never told him.
- No, we never told him.

29:23.127 --> 29:24.170
- No.
- He just thought it was

29:24.253 --> 29:25.588
- a real bird.
- Yeah.

29:25.672 --> 29:27.173
It was insane
that we were part of that.

29:27.256 --> 29:28.925
You know, I do not know
of another human being

29:29.008 --> 29:30.510
that could have started
the series in the way you did.

29:30.593 --> 29:31.969
Well, that...
that makes me feel great.

29:32.053 --> 29:33.304
I've always felt guilty
about leaving.

29:33.388 --> 29:34.722
- I really did.
- Don't.

29:34.806 --> 29:37.308
When I said goodbye
to you guys, I was like,

29:37.392 --> 29:39.394
"I can't believe
I'm leaving these guys."

29:39.477 --> 29:41.229
And I think you honestly...
I don't think you ever

29:41.312 --> 29:44.148
get enough credit for, like,
what you achieved

29:44.232 --> 29:46.275
on those first two
and with all of us,

29:46.359 --> 29:47.819
and so thank you
so much for that.

29:47.902 --> 29:50.571
It's been the greatest
experience of my life.

29:53.241 --> 29:56.661
<i>You fail to recognize
that it matters not</i>

29:56.744 --> 29:59.956
<i>what someone is born...</i>

30:00.039 --> 30:02.917
<i>but what they grow to be.</i>

30:11.676 --> 30:14.345
Hello.

30:17.348 --> 30:19.767
Oh, thank you for coming.

30:19.851 --> 30:21.352
Thanks for chatting.

30:23.020 --> 30:26.482
Who is that? That man.

30:26.566 --> 30:28.109
Who is that?

30:28.192 --> 30:30.820
<i>That is Sirius Black, that is.</i>

30:32.530 --> 30:35.283
<i>Sirius Black is an essential
character for Harry.</i>

30:35.366 --> 30:36.784
It's part of Jo's themes of

30:36.868 --> 30:38.619
"Don't judge a book
by its cover," you know?

30:38.703 --> 30:40.455
The image of Sirius Black
as a criminal

30:40.538 --> 30:42.665
is one that's presented
to Harry.

30:42.749 --> 30:44.792
We have a killer
on the loose.

30:44.876 --> 30:46.794
Sirius Black, you mean?

30:46.878 --> 30:48.588
But what's he got
to do with me?

30:48.671 --> 30:50.882
<i>And yet,
when Harry meets him</i>

30:50.965 --> 30:53.009
<i>and through the course
of the third film,</i>

30:53.092 --> 30:56.804
he comes to learn that he's not
who he has been told he was.

30:56.888 --> 30:58.639
He's somebody very different.

30:58.723 --> 31:01.601
<i>And Gary is such
a remarkable actor.</i>

31:01.684 --> 31:03.644
One of the reasons we
chose him is he obviously

31:03.728 --> 31:06.147
has the potential for darkness,

31:06.230 --> 31:11.819
but he has such soul
and has such a warmth within.

31:11.903 --> 31:13.654
Can I ask you, when were...

31:13.738 --> 31:15.698
were you first
approached to be Sirius?

31:15.782 --> 31:17.325
I was aware of Harry Potter,

31:17.408 --> 31:20.828
but it... it was very much
a sort of kids' thing.

31:20.912 --> 31:24.332
People were telling me to read
the books and I had kids,

31:24.415 --> 31:27.335
so it was gonna be
in my universe somewhere.

31:27.418 --> 31:31.214
And then they were taking
a slightly darker approach.

31:31.297 --> 31:32.882
- Yeah.
- The book was interesting.

31:32.965 --> 31:35.468
I met Alfonso,
and I think at the time,

31:35.551 --> 31:36.844
he was the main attraction.

31:36.928 --> 31:38.554
Now, remember, guys,
that you have to

31:38.638 --> 31:40.807
- take care of your frogs.
- Yeah. Don't worry.

31:40.890 --> 31:44.435
For "Azkaban,"
it's a coming of age.

31:44.519 --> 31:47.772
<i>They're passing the threshold
between childhood</i>

31:47.855 --> 31:50.608
<i>and their teenage years.</i>

31:50.691 --> 31:54.028
In the first two,
Harry is still a child.

31:54.111 --> 32:00.368
<i>There is a greater optimism
around the tone itself.</i>

32:00.451 --> 32:03.120
<i>Nevertheless,
when he turns 13,</i>

32:03.204 --> 32:04.455
<i>there's a big cloud</i>

32:04.539 --> 32:07.375
that overshadows
everything around Harry,

32:07.458 --> 32:11.045
and we needed to convey that
also stylistically.

32:19.762 --> 32:21.889
What's going on?

32:21.973 --> 32:25.309
Don't know,
maybe we've broken down.

32:33.359 --> 32:38.155
<i>"Prisoner of Azkaban" felt
like a whole new era, really.</i>

32:38.239 --> 32:40.908
It was a much darker
kind of story.

32:40.992 --> 32:43.744
There was a lot of kind of
quite adult themes in it.

32:43.828 --> 32:46.247
<i>The descriptions
that JK Rowling</i>

32:46.330 --> 32:49.083
has of the dementors
are very scary,

32:49.166 --> 32:53.129
<i>and I really wanted to convey
the sense that the dementors,</i>

32:53.212 --> 32:57.592
what they do is they suck
all the joy away,

32:57.675 --> 33:02.013
<i>that they were sucking
an essence of Harry.</i>

33:02.096 --> 33:05.099
<i>But I think that the most
important piece</i>

33:05.182 --> 33:08.352
<i>to achieve that
was Dan's performance.</i>

33:09.896 --> 33:12.940
When was "Azkaban"...
how old were you?

33:13.024 --> 33:14.275
14.

33:14.358 --> 33:15.568
- Really?
- Yeah.

33:15.651 --> 33:17.153
- When we first met?
- Yeah.

33:17.236 --> 33:20.615
I think I had a natural
sort of paternal thing.

33:26.787 --> 33:28.831
Are you going to kill me,
Harry?

33:28.915 --> 33:30.750
The first person I remember
being, like,

33:30.833 --> 33:32.668
in order of when they came in
was Gary.

33:32.752 --> 33:34.253
I remember that. I remember...

33:34.337 --> 33:36.797
I remember you
giving me the Gary chat.

33:36.881 --> 33:39.467
Yeah, you were like, "Listen,
Emma, you need to be cool,

33:39.550 --> 33:42.011
"because Gary Oldman...
it's a really big deal,

33:42.094 --> 33:44.597
and you need to be cool,"
and I was like, "Okay."

33:44.680 --> 33:46.349
And which was... which
was really a projection

33:46.432 --> 33:48.100
of my own fears
'cause I was like,

33:48.184 --> 33:51.103
"Dan, you need to be cool.
This guy's a big deal."

33:52.229 --> 33:54.815
<i>Dan was first a bit daunted.</i>

33:54.899 --> 33:58.319
And Gary was amazingly generous
as a person,

33:58.402 --> 34:01.197
but also as an actor,
and immediately embrace him

34:01.280 --> 34:04.325
<i>and include him
in... in the acting process.</i>

34:04.408 --> 34:07.620
It was really sweet
to... to see the two of them.

34:07.703 --> 34:12.166
And it was almost as if it was
mirroring that relationship

34:12.248 --> 34:15.210
<i>because, in many ways,
Harry has made a totem</i>

34:15.293 --> 34:17.170
<i>out of Sirius Black.</i>

34:17.254 --> 34:20.466
That totem
that is kind of unapproachable

34:20.549 --> 34:22.510
and in many ways scary.

34:22.592 --> 34:24.804
<i>And then that was not unlike
in the film</i>

34:24.887 --> 34:27.431
<i>that when they discover
who they truly are,</i>

34:27.514 --> 34:30.016
<i>is when suddenly
there's an amazing bond.</i>

34:30.101 --> 34:32.268
You saw them between takes

34:32.353 --> 34:35.106
sitting with each other,
talking and laughing.

34:35.188 --> 34:38.025
<i>And you could see in the way
that Dan looked at Gary</i>

34:38.109 --> 34:41.862
<i>the adulation and the respect
that he had for him.</i>

34:41.946 --> 34:43.531
All the stuff in
the Shrieking Shack at the end,

34:43.614 --> 34:45.199
I feel like me and Rupert
and Emma were just, like,

34:45.282 --> 34:46.409
watching tennis in that scene
just being like,

34:46.492 --> 34:47.952
"This is acting, guys.

34:48.034 --> 34:50.036
This is what we all need
to be working towards."

34:50.121 --> 34:52.206
<i>There was Tim Spall,</i>

34:52.289 --> 34:54.166
- <i>the one and only Alan Rickman.</i>
- <i>Yeah.</i>

34:54.250 --> 34:58.212
David Thewlis, you,
Emma, Rupert.

34:58.296 --> 35:00.047
It's really nice of you
to include me, Emma, and Rupert

35:00.131 --> 35:01.173
in that group.

35:01.257 --> 35:02.633
<i>To watch you guys act but also</i>

35:02.717 --> 35:04.343
<i>just watching
you guys as people</i>

35:04.427 --> 35:06.554
and just watching these,
like, incredible actors

35:06.637 --> 35:08.222
who were just like,
"Oh, yeah, no.

35:08.305 --> 35:10.141
"You're just people
and you'd have fun in between

35:10.224 --> 35:11.976
<i>and the whole process
doesn't have to be painful."</i>

35:12.059 --> 35:13.936
<i>It can be intense
and you showed me the wonders</i>

35:14.020 --> 35:16.397
<i>of that sometimes as well
and that was really important.</i>

35:16.480 --> 35:18.065
- Let's kill him!
- Wait.

35:18.149 --> 35:23.362
I did my waiting!
12 years of it!

35:23.446 --> 35:25.156
In Azkaban!

35:25.239 --> 35:26.615
I have never done a scene

35:26.699 --> 35:29.035
with such an amazing cast
in my life.

35:29.118 --> 35:30.703
<i>It's a very long scene.</i>

35:30.786 --> 35:32.663
<i>It's a scene in which
there are a lot of twists</i>

35:32.747 --> 35:35.207
<i>inside the scene,
and it was so much fun.</i>

35:35.291 --> 35:38.878
It's an intense scene in which
a lot of things are at stake.

35:38.961 --> 35:41.422
No! I trusted you!

35:41.505 --> 35:45.009
<i>And you can see...
Rupert and Emma and Dan...</i>

35:45.092 --> 35:48.095
<i>that they are completely
committed to this scene.</i>

35:48.179 --> 35:51.599
I love it. I-I have such
a great memory of it.

35:51.682 --> 35:54.226
I told Dumbledore
you were helping an old friend

35:54.310 --> 35:56.771
into the castle,
and now here's the proof.

35:56.854 --> 35:58.814
Brilliant, Snape.
Once again,

35:58.898 --> 36:00.816
you've put your keen and
penetrating mind to the task,

36:00.900 --> 36:03.110
and as usual,
come to the wrong conclusion.

36:03.986 --> 36:05.821
<i>I always loved
the character of Sirius.</i>

36:05.905 --> 36:07.615
I love the relationship
Harry and Sirius have.

36:07.698 --> 36:11.577
He's like this cool uncle,
but also older brother figure.

36:11.660 --> 36:14.288
<i>He's painted
as this villainous guy</i>

36:14.372 --> 36:16.874
<i>and then has the switch
where you go,</i>

36:16.957 --> 36:19.960
<i>"Oh, he was set up
and he's a good guy."</i>

36:20.044 --> 36:21.462
<i>And he's so kind
and so warm...</i>

36:21.545 --> 36:22.797
- And he's warm and kind...
- And cool.

36:22.880 --> 36:24.673
- And he's kinda cool.
- Yeah.

36:24.757 --> 36:27.676
I wish I'd had
the whole picture.

36:27.760 --> 36:29.678
You know, we only
ever found out book...

36:29.762 --> 36:31.097
Yeah, book by book.

36:31.180 --> 36:32.598
- I don't know whether you...
- I did not.

36:32.681 --> 36:34.058
Because you were
Harry Potter, you had a...

36:34.141 --> 36:35.392
Just Rickman.
Rickman did. That was it.

36:35.476 --> 36:37.103
- Rickman?
- He had the inside line.

36:37.186 --> 36:38.395
He worked that well.

36:38.479 --> 36:40.189
He very, very early
said to Jo,

36:40.272 --> 36:42.733
he was like, "I think I need
to know what happens."

36:42.817 --> 36:44.151
I need to know.

36:45.402 --> 36:48.739
Give me a reason. I beg you.

36:48.823 --> 36:50.449
<i>Rickman would have an in,
wouldn't he?</i>

36:50.533 --> 36:51.784
He did, yeah.

36:51.867 --> 36:53.327
And he never told Chris,
never told anyone.

36:53.410 --> 36:54.787
He would... Chris would
literally say to him,

36:54.870 --> 36:56.080
"Why are you doing that
like that?"

36:56.163 --> 36:57.623
He'd say,
"I'll tell you later."

37:02.169 --> 37:04.880
Yeah, "You'll find out
on a need-to-know basis."

37:04.964 --> 37:06.382
Wait a decade.

37:06.465 --> 37:10.261
Dan was not a child actor.
Was another fellow actor.

37:10.344 --> 37:12.513
Alfonso was like,
"Now you're teenagers,

37:12.596 --> 37:14.014
and I'm gonna treat you
like a teenager."

37:14.098 --> 37:15.558
And he was the first one
who, like,

37:15.641 --> 37:18.018
- assigned us homework.
- Yeah.

37:18.102 --> 37:19.395
Loosen up, loosen up.

37:19.478 --> 37:21.313
<i>He wanted to get to know us,</i>

37:21.397 --> 37:24.358
so he set us this exercise
where he asked us

37:24.441 --> 37:26.235
to write an essay in character.

37:28.946 --> 37:31.198
<i>He was like,
"You know these characters</i>

37:31.282 --> 37:33.534
<i>"at this point better
than I'm ever gonna be able</i>

37:33.617 --> 37:36.495
<i>to understand who they are,
so you tell me."</i>

37:36.579 --> 37:38.122
<i>And after about, sort of,</i>

37:38.205 --> 37:40.082
<i>a half a side of A4,
I was like,</i>

37:40.166 --> 37:42.168
"I feel like I've pretty much
covered everything.

37:42.251 --> 37:45.462
<i>"Like, Jo has written
a good 500 pages about this,</i>

37:45.546 --> 37:48.048
"but I feel like this one
pretty much sums it up.

37:48.132 --> 37:50.384
Great, okay. Yeah, cool.
Proud of that. Bring that in."

37:50.468 --> 37:54.555
Of course, Emma writes,
like, 12 pages,

37:54.638 --> 37:56.015
like, beautifully written.

37:56.098 --> 38:00.186
Rupert didn't deliver
anything.

38:00.269 --> 38:01.729
I didn't do it.

38:01.812 --> 38:03.564
And I said, "Rupert,
where's your assignment?"

38:03.647 --> 38:09.111
He says, "Well, uh, I thought
that Ron wouldn't do it..."

38:09.195 --> 38:11.989
"So I didn't do it."

38:12.072 --> 38:14.241
I mean, luckily,
Alfonso kind of saw

38:14.325 --> 38:16.118
that it was very in character
for... for...

38:16.202 --> 38:17.536
for me not to have done it.

38:17.620 --> 38:21.081
Rupert is Ron.

38:21.165 --> 38:23.876
<i>It's just Ron 100%.</i>

38:23.959 --> 38:28.422
Emma is just such
an effortless actor.

38:28.506 --> 38:30.299
<i>She prepares a lot.</i>

38:30.382 --> 38:32.760
When you're doing the scenes,
it's as if everything

38:32.843 --> 38:34.428
is just flowing out of her.

38:34.511 --> 38:37.556
<i>The truth of the matter
is that they are great actors.</i>

38:37.640 --> 38:41.685
<i>Sirius Black
finds a redemption</i>

38:41.769 --> 38:46.190
<i>by having Harry understanding
who he truly is.</i>

38:46.273 --> 38:48.192
<i>It's a moment of...
of great liberation,</i>

38:48.275 --> 38:49.944
<i>of great freedom,</i>

38:50.027 --> 38:54.031
and all of this is conveyed
symbolically in the two of them

38:54.114 --> 38:57.743
flying in the night
under the silver moon.

39:02.623 --> 39:04.458
<i>It was like a family,
wasn't it?</i>

39:04.541 --> 39:05.668
Yeah.

39:05.751 --> 39:08.045
More than any
other experience.

39:08.128 --> 39:09.797
You never have that
in the movies

39:09.880 --> 39:11.632
because you work
with a bunch of people

39:11.715 --> 39:13.217
and you get friendly with them

39:13.300 --> 39:15.928
and then most of them
you would never see again.

39:16.011 --> 39:19.223
But with "Potter," you would
come... you would come back

39:19.306 --> 39:23.852
and that's what made it,
amongst many things,

39:23.936 --> 39:26.021
- what made it very special.
- Yeah.

39:26.105 --> 39:28.357
It just feels like,
you know, being in these,

39:28.440 --> 39:30.818
you get to be a part
of film history.

39:39.576 --> 39:41.495
Hogwarts has been chosen

39:41.578 --> 39:44.999
to host
the Triwizard Tournament.

39:47.626 --> 39:49.128
"The Goblet of Fire"

39:49.211 --> 39:52.172
during all of
the Triwizard Tournament stuff,

39:52.256 --> 39:57.094
<i>it was so lovely to be
surprised and blown away</i>

39:57.177 --> 40:02.850
and, like, taken away
by the magic of the scenes

40:02.933 --> 40:04.184
and to be surprised.

40:04.268 --> 40:05.519
<i>Like, I remember seeing
the Beauxbatons</i>

40:05.602 --> 40:07.396
<i>come and do their entrance</i>

40:07.479 --> 40:09.690
<i>and the Durmstrangs.</i>

40:09.773 --> 40:11.525
It was really cool.

40:13.277 --> 40:15.696
<i>With the fourth film,
we wanted a British director.</i>

40:15.779 --> 40:17.406
We wanted something
quite theatrical.

40:17.489 --> 40:18.824
Cut, thank you very much.

40:18.907 --> 40:22.911
Mike is just this excited,

40:22.995 --> 40:25.914
loud, passionate man.

40:27.583 --> 40:29.418
<i>He was a perfect director
for that film.</i>

40:29.501 --> 40:32.004
It was a really, like,
bombastic,

40:32.087 --> 40:36.008
<i>action-packed, wonderful,
eccentric film.</i>

40:36.091 --> 40:37.676
I love Mike. He was great.

40:37.760 --> 40:39.720
<i>I mean, he was almost like
he was from the books.</i>

40:39.803 --> 40:42.556
He was like
a Hogwarts character.

40:42.639 --> 40:44.850
The fourth book
is the biggest of them.

40:44.933 --> 40:47.561
It's about 900 pages.
It's a doorstop.

40:47.644 --> 40:49.188
It's a house brick.

40:49.271 --> 40:50.647
Action!

40:50.731 --> 40:53.651
<i>And I thought,
if it's really gonna nail</i>

40:53.734 --> 40:55.569
the little darlings
to their seats,

40:55.652 --> 41:01.408
then it has to have this great,
big, energetic core to it.

41:01.492 --> 41:04.745
<i>He was just this kind of,
like, firecracker of energy.</i>

41:04.828 --> 41:06.413
<i>He'd get so excited by things.</i>

41:06.497 --> 41:08.749
<i>And there was this kind of
really endearing,</i>

41:08.832 --> 41:10.584
like, childlike quality
to... to him.

41:10.667 --> 41:13.420
<i>He loved the humor as well
and would always</i>

41:13.504 --> 41:15.339
<i>try and find it
in every scene.</i>

41:15.422 --> 41:18.175
It was probably only
a couple of films in

41:18.258 --> 41:20.260
that I sort of started
to feel nervous.

41:20.344 --> 41:22.096
- And I remember...
- It was Mike's change

41:22.179 --> 41:23.430
when... when Columbus left.

41:23.514 --> 41:24.848
It was definitely
a bit of a different...

41:24.932 --> 41:26.392
Yeah,
it was a different vibe.

41:26.475 --> 41:28.435
- Mike Newell.
- Mike treated us like adults.

41:28.519 --> 41:29.686
- That was it.
- Yeah.

41:29.770 --> 41:31.605
- He did, I suppose.
- Yeah.

41:31.689 --> 41:33.315
We did have fun on set.

41:36.693 --> 41:40.072
<i>The Weasley twins,
whom I-I was very fond of,</i>

41:40.155 --> 41:42.658
<i>they had to fight.</i>

41:42.741 --> 41:44.952
We were doing the scene
when Fred and George

41:45.035 --> 41:47.121
are rejected from entering
the Triwizard Tournament.

41:47.204 --> 41:49.873
<i>And then we had these wigs
on and beards on.</i>

41:49.957 --> 41:51.709
<i>What looked like old men.</i>

41:51.792 --> 41:53.544
<i>And Mike said, "Okay, so I
think you guys will be really</i>

41:53.627 --> 41:54.878
<i>"annoyed with each other.
I think you should have</i>

41:54.962 --> 41:56.422
<i>a good fight about this."</i>

41:56.505 --> 42:00.467
These two were sort of,
um, pressing about at it.

42:00.551 --> 42:02.136
Cut!

42:02.219 --> 42:04.638
<i>And I said, "No, come on boys,
really, it's a fight."</i>

42:04.721 --> 42:05.973
<i>Mike just came over.
He said,</i>

42:06.056 --> 42:07.141
<i>"No, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no."</i>

42:07.224 --> 42:08.684
Okay, who wants to fight?

42:08.767 --> 42:11.270
And like an idiot,
I was like, "Oh, yeah, okay."

42:11.353 --> 42:14.523
Well, of course,
I was a tubby 60-year-old gent

42:14.606 --> 42:15.983
at that stage.

42:16.066 --> 42:20.195
Um, and, uh, I-I really
shouldn't have done it.

42:20.279 --> 42:22.865
And so he dived on me
and, like,

42:22.948 --> 42:25.367
just went like this,

42:25.451 --> 42:27.911
to which I said, "Okay."
So I did the same to him.

42:27.995 --> 42:30.873
<i>I-I remember gripping him
'round the waist</i>

42:30.956 --> 42:33.417
<i>and trying to fling him about
and so forth</i>

42:33.500 --> 42:36.003
and cracked a couple of ribs.

42:36.086 --> 42:39.423
And so was in absolute agony
from... from then on.

42:39.506 --> 42:41.925
But of course,
the wonderful thing was

42:42.009 --> 42:44.636
that I had made
a complete twit of myself

42:44.720 --> 42:47.431
and everybody felt
much better for that.

42:47.514 --> 42:51.101
You know when you shouldn't
break a director's rib?

43:02.446 --> 43:03.697
<i>In "The Goblet of Fire,"</i>

43:03.780 --> 43:06.492
that film is just all
about teenagers,

43:06.575 --> 43:08.202
you know, having crushes
for the first time,

43:08.285 --> 43:10.996
asking someone to the date,
to the Yule Ball.

43:11.079 --> 43:13.415
<i>They just mirrored all those
kind of awkward phases</i>

43:13.499 --> 43:14.875
you go through as a teenager,

43:14.958 --> 43:16.543
and they really
felt like that, too,

43:16.627 --> 43:19.046
because we were literally
having the same experiences.

43:19.129 --> 43:21.924
The amount of, um, like,
prep and coaching

43:22.007 --> 43:23.509
Emma and I would give
each other on, like,

43:23.592 --> 43:25.385
texting to the opposite sex...
like, if we...

43:25.469 --> 43:26.929
if she was texting a boy
or I was texting a girl,

43:27.012 --> 43:28.764
I'd be like, "She sent me
this many kisses back.

43:28.847 --> 43:30.557
What do I do?
This is a nightmare."

43:30.641 --> 43:34.228
We had that kind of older
brother, younger sister thing.

43:34.311 --> 43:36.021
<i>It was a very
interesting film</i>

43:36.104 --> 43:38.190
in terms of a lot of hormones
flying around.

43:39.608 --> 43:40.943
<i>There was crushes,</i>

43:41.026 --> 43:42.528
<i>and people
went out with each other</i>

43:42.611 --> 43:44.404
and broke up and...
just like you do in...

43:44.488 --> 43:45.781
like I used to do at school.

43:45.864 --> 43:47.991
Um, it was exactly
the same environment,

43:48.075 --> 43:50.661
<i>but it was just in a Defense
Against the Dark Arts class.</i>

43:53.872 --> 43:57.334
That film was probably
peak hormone, at least for me.

44:01.004 --> 44:02.589
<i>It was exactly
what you'd expect.</i>

44:02.673 --> 44:04.258
And especially, like,
the fourth film was the one

44:04.341 --> 44:07.302
with, like, the Beauxbatons
and the Durmstrangs,

44:07.386 --> 44:09.680
<i>so, like, you had a bunch of,</i>

44:09.763 --> 44:11.431
<i>like, hormonal teenagers
anyway,</i>

44:11.515 --> 44:14.434
and then, like, bring in two
massive groups of new people,

44:14.518 --> 44:17.271
all of them are, like,
purposefully hot for the film.

44:17.354 --> 44:19.898
Um, so it's, yeah,
it was that...

44:19.982 --> 44:21.608
that film was, yeah,
it was all kicking off.

44:21.692 --> 44:24.319
Why do they have to travel
in packs?

44:24.403 --> 44:27.281
<i>He is just, like,
a slightly awkward teenage boy</i>

44:27.364 --> 44:29.491
<i>in a very unremarkable way,</i>

44:29.575 --> 44:30.951
which I suppose feels
sort of remarkable

44:31.034 --> 44:32.703
for a hero character
in something.

44:32.786 --> 44:34.288
You slay dragons.

44:34.371 --> 44:35.956
If you can't get a date,
who can?

44:36.039 --> 44:37.583
I think I'd take the dragon
right now.

44:37.666 --> 44:41.253
Jo wrote him very endearingly
in those years,

44:41.336 --> 44:46.383
and I feel like it did not
take a huge acting stretch

44:46.466 --> 44:51.471
for me to tap into my awkward,
nerdy, teenage side.

44:51.555 --> 44:53.974
- Cho.
- Yes?

44:54.057 --> 44:57.185
Um, I just wondered if you...
I just wondered

44:57.269 --> 44:59.479
if maybe you wanted
to go to the ball with me?

44:59.563 --> 45:02.107
Sorry, I didn't catch that.

45:02.190 --> 45:04.318
It obviously was
a coming-of-age story.

45:08.447 --> 45:10.032
One of the... the big,
big sequences

45:10.115 --> 45:11.908
was the Christmas ball.

45:11.992 --> 45:18.665
The Yule Ball is,
first and foremost, a dance.

45:18.749 --> 45:22.628
<i>The scene when the students
are learning to dance,</i>

45:22.711 --> 45:24.004
it was pretty much like
a typical

45:24.087 --> 45:25.505
school dance of that age.

45:25.589 --> 45:27.966
You've got girls on one side,
boys on the other.

45:28.050 --> 45:30.677
<i>We were in a big room
in Oxford.</i>

45:30.761 --> 45:32.638
Maggie's right in the middle,
and she says,

45:32.721 --> 45:34.514
