59:51.954 --> 59:53.164
I will say that that was

59:53.247 --> 59:54.373
an interesting point
for all of us

59:54.457 --> 59:55.833
as, like, younger actors.

59:55.917 --> 59:58.252
'Cause there was
a certain group, like Maggie...

59:58.336 --> 01:00:00.421
- Yeah
- David Bradley, and Alan.

01:00:00.505 --> 01:00:02.715
They had known us
when we were 10 or 11.

01:00:02.798 --> 01:00:05.176
And when you came in, by that
point, I was like 15, 16.

01:00:05.259 --> 01:00:07.512
So, like, you
and Gary and David, like,

01:00:07.595 --> 01:00:09.889
would treat us more
like adults; I loved it.

01:00:09.972 --> 01:00:11.933
You saw in us, that, like,
a few of us were, like,

01:00:12.016 --> 01:00:13.726
kind of ready to be like,
"Could you push me?

01:00:13.809 --> 01:00:15.895
Like, we... we wanna try
and be actors too."

01:00:23.736 --> 01:00:26.405
<i>By the time we get
to "Order of the Phoenix,"</i>

01:00:26.489 --> 01:00:29.075
<i>the world is becoming
more political.</i>

01:00:29.158 --> 01:00:31.536
<i>And I felt
we needed a director</i>

01:00:31.619 --> 01:00:34.247
<i>who could handle that
in an entertaining way.</i>

01:00:34.330 --> 01:00:36.791
David Yates works
so well with actors,

01:00:36.874 --> 01:00:39.835
really pushes them
in all the right way.

01:00:39.919 --> 01:00:43.256
Progress for the sake
of progress

01:00:43.339 --> 01:00:45.883
must be discouraged.

01:00:45.967 --> 01:00:49.303
David was just such
a sweet, kind of gentle guy

01:00:49.387 --> 01:00:52.682
<i>that really cared so much
about all of these characters.</i>

01:00:52.765 --> 01:00:54.433
<i>And also, I'd get
a lot of kinda one-on-one</i>

01:00:54.517 --> 01:00:55.893
<i>with David Yates.</i>

01:00:55.977 --> 01:00:57.937
<i>I went into
"Order of the Phoenix"</i>

01:00:58.020 --> 01:00:59.939
<i>with the young actors in mind
and sort of thinking about</i>

01:01:00.022 --> 01:01:02.275
<i>how we sort of grow
the whole thing up</i>

01:01:02.358 --> 01:01:04.610
<i>and make it
a little bit more adult</i>

01:01:04.694 --> 01:01:08.072
and sort of thematic
and a little darker.

01:01:12.660 --> 01:01:14.954
<i>It needed to expand
and get bigger</i>

01:01:15.037 --> 01:01:17.331
<i>and more and more frightening.</i>

01:01:19.125 --> 01:01:21.168
Ah!

01:01:21.252 --> 01:01:24.964
<i>There was a big increase
in scale and complexity,</i>

01:01:25.047 --> 01:01:28.593
from being childish
to influencing events

01:01:28.676 --> 01:01:31.596
and being part
of the big world.

01:01:31.679 --> 01:01:33.973
He's just a boy.

01:01:34.056 --> 01:01:35.391
You say much more,
and you might as well

01:01:35.474 --> 01:01:36.892
induct him into the Order
straight away.

01:01:36.976 --> 01:01:38.519
Good. I want to join.

01:01:38.603 --> 01:01:40.605
If Voldemort's raising an army,
then I want to fight.

01:01:44.734 --> 01:01:48.029
<i>When I started, one thing
that David and the studio</i>

01:01:48.112 --> 01:01:49.822
spoke to me about was,

01:01:49.905 --> 01:01:54.744
Emma is not sure she wants to
come back to do another Potter.

01:01:55.578 --> 01:01:56.954
Oh, Harry.

01:01:59.915 --> 01:02:02.668
People definitely forget
what she took on

01:02:02.752 --> 01:02:04.837
and how gracefully she did it.

01:02:05.921 --> 01:02:08.758
<i>Dan and Rupert,
they had each other.</i>

01:02:08.841 --> 01:02:10.843
<i>I had my cronies,</i>

01:02:10.926 --> 01:02:12.678
whereas Emma
was not only younger,

01:02:12.762 --> 01:02:16.474
she was... she was by herself.

01:02:16.557 --> 01:02:20.603
I did find a diary entry
that was kind of like, hmm.

01:02:21.437 --> 01:02:25.399
<i>I could see that,
at times, I was lonely.</i>

01:02:25.483 --> 01:02:27.193
We never talked
about it on the film

01:02:27.276 --> 01:02:28.903
because we were all just kids.

01:02:29.987 --> 01:02:31.530
<i>As a 14-year-old boy,</i>

01:02:31.614 --> 01:02:33.199
I was never gonna turn around
to another 14-year-old

01:02:33.282 --> 01:02:34.533
and be like,
"Hey, how you doing?

01:02:34.617 --> 01:02:36.410
Like, is everything okay?"

01:02:36.494 --> 01:02:38.037
<i>So "Order of the Phoenix."</i>

01:02:38.120 --> 01:02:40.206
Was when things started
getting spicy for all of us.

01:02:40.289 --> 01:02:42.541
Mm, but you were
considering pulling out.

01:02:42.625 --> 01:02:44.210
I never really spoke
to you about this.

01:02:44.293 --> 01:02:46.879
Yeah. I think, um...

01:02:46.962 --> 01:02:48.422
- I think I was scared.
- Yeah.

01:02:48.506 --> 01:02:50.049
I don't know if...
if you ever felt like

01:02:50.132 --> 01:02:51.384
it got to a tipping point
when you were like...

01:02:51.467 --> 01:02:53.052
Oh, absolutely.

01:02:53.135 --> 01:02:54.428
This is kinda forever now.

01:02:54.512 --> 01:02:56.430
Yeah.
No, I had moments like that.

01:02:56.514 --> 01:02:57.723
Kind of all the way through.

01:02:59.517 --> 01:03:03.104
<i>I would say I had kind of
similar feelings to Emma.</i>

01:03:03.729 --> 01:03:05.940
Kind of contemplating
what life would be like

01:03:06.023 --> 01:03:08.567
if I called it a day, but...

01:03:08.651 --> 01:03:10.861
<i>we never really spoke
about... I guess we were just</i>

01:03:10.945 --> 01:03:12.738
<i>kind of going through it
at our own pace.</i>

01:03:12.822 --> 01:03:14.532
We were kind of in the moment.

01:03:14.615 --> 01:03:18.536
At the time, it just didn't
really occur to us

01:03:18.619 --> 01:03:22.289
that we were all kind of having
similar... similar feelings.

01:03:23.916 --> 01:03:26.377
Yeah, um...

01:03:26.460 --> 01:03:30.256
the fame thing had
finally hit home in a big way.

01:03:32.133 --> 01:03:35.469
No one had to convince me
to see it through.

01:03:36.929 --> 01:03:39.265
<i>The fans genuinely
wanted us to succeed,</i>

01:03:39.348 --> 01:03:42.768
and we all genuinely
had each other's backs.

01:03:42.852 --> 01:03:44.061
How great is that?

01:03:53.529 --> 01:03:55.281
<i>It's always amazing
that these films</i>

01:03:55.364 --> 01:03:57.283
<i>mean so much to them,
they...'cause we...</i>

01:03:57.366 --> 01:04:00.244
<i>they kind of grew up
alongside us and helped them</i>

01:04:00.327 --> 01:04:02.663
<i>with some really difficult
things in their lives.</i>

01:04:02.747 --> 01:04:06.041
And I'm just very proud
to be a part of something

01:04:06.125 --> 01:04:09.920
that means so much to so many.

01:04:16.010 --> 01:04:17.178
I've been thinking about

01:04:17.261 --> 01:04:19.472
something Dumbledore
said to me.

01:04:19.555 --> 01:04:20.806
What's that?

01:04:21.724 --> 01:04:24.727
That even though we've got
a fight ahead of us,

01:04:24.810 --> 01:04:27.271
we've got one thing
that Voldemort doesn't have.

01:04:28.189 --> 01:04:29.315
Yeah?

01:04:31.442 --> 01:04:33.652
Something worth fighting for.

01:04:36.947 --> 01:04:39.825
My son, Billy, we used
to watch them every night.

01:04:39.909 --> 01:04:41.786
You know, if he got
the Sunday night blues,

01:04:41.869 --> 01:04:44.163
he was watching a Potter movie.

01:04:44.246 --> 01:04:45.664
That was his safe place.

01:04:45.748 --> 01:04:47.374
I'm really looking forward
to watching the films

01:04:47.458 --> 01:04:49.335
with my hypothetical children
one day.

01:04:49.418 --> 01:04:51.879
It's massive, the impact.
It is extraordinary.

01:04:51.962 --> 01:04:53.172
It is unbelievable.

01:04:56.884 --> 01:05:00.137
I was writing to JK Rowling
since I was about 11 years old

01:05:00.221 --> 01:05:01.847
<i>to say thank you to her
to say,</i>

01:05:01.931 --> 01:05:04.809
I would find life a bit
hopeless without Harry Potter.

01:05:04.892 --> 01:05:06.977
<i>Luckily for me,
she read the letter</i>

01:05:07.061 --> 01:05:08.521
<i>and responded to it.</i>

01:05:08.604 --> 01:05:12.525
So I'm one of the very lucky
few people who can say

01:05:12.608 --> 01:05:14.401
JK Rowling was my pen friend.

01:05:18.030 --> 01:05:20.074
<i>The first part
of the audition</i>

01:05:20.157 --> 01:05:21.742
is this crazy open call.

01:05:21.826 --> 01:05:23.869
Literally, anyone can come.

01:05:25.329 --> 01:05:26.872
That's my ticket.
Off we go.

01:05:26.956 --> 01:05:27.915
Let's go to London.

01:05:27.998 --> 01:05:29.625
We fly, of course.

01:05:29.708 --> 01:05:33.128
<i>And there would be thousands
of people lining up.</i>

01:05:33.212 --> 01:05:36.090
<i>I remember Dan very vividly.</i>

01:05:36.173 --> 01:05:37.550
<i>It was on my screen test.</i>

01:05:37.633 --> 01:05:38.968
Mistletoe.

01:05:40.511 --> 01:05:42.096
I remember him talking to me,

01:05:42.179 --> 01:05:43.806
and I kept forgetting
that I have to talk back to him

01:05:43.889 --> 01:05:46.559
because I'm so used
to watching him on a screen.

01:05:46.642 --> 01:05:48.143
So I would just
kind of be like...

01:05:49.103 --> 01:05:51.063
I kind of think
that contributed to the whole

01:05:51.146 --> 01:05:55.860
Luna Lovegood vibe,
because she is a bit spacy.

01:05:55.943 --> 01:05:57.319
Hello, everyone.

01:05:58.571 --> 01:06:00.322
You look dreadful, Ron.

01:06:00.406 --> 01:06:04.201
And then he found
this secret world of odd bots,

01:06:04.285 --> 01:06:07.329
of misfits, of people
who had this strange power

01:06:07.413 --> 01:06:09.915
but who still had
enormous humanity

01:06:09.999 --> 01:06:11.750
<i>and depth and vulnerability.</i>

01:06:11.834 --> 01:06:13.794
<i>The movies kind of
gave people permission</i>

01:06:13.878 --> 01:06:15.462
<i>to accept parts of themselves.</i>

01:06:15.546 --> 01:06:18.591
<i>So it was quite liberating
to see your oddness</i>

01:06:18.674 --> 01:06:21.760
as a superpower
represented on-screen.

01:06:21.844 --> 01:06:23.762
I remember
when I first met you all...

01:06:23.846 --> 01:06:26.932
biggest bunch of misfits
that I ever set eyes on,

01:06:27.016 --> 01:06:28.601
and here we all are.

01:06:28.684 --> 01:06:30.144
We're still
a bunch of misfits.

01:06:30.227 --> 01:06:32.980
Well, maybe,
but we've all got each other.

01:06:34.023 --> 01:06:35.691
I was not good at school.

01:06:35.774 --> 01:06:37.484
You'd be better off with
"Goshawk's Guide to Herbology."

01:06:37.568 --> 01:06:39.403
I didn't have
a huge amount of friends.

01:06:40.237 --> 01:06:42.364
Watch where you're going,
Longbottom.

01:06:44.199 --> 01:06:45.743
<i>I think it's great
to be a misfit.</i>

01:06:45.826 --> 01:06:48.120
And I think that's possibly
why it's so popular.

01:06:48.203 --> 01:06:50.789
Everyone wants to know
that they do belong.

01:06:50.873 --> 01:06:53.334
<i>It's a great relief
of loneliness, I think.</i>

01:06:53.417 --> 01:06:54.877
<i>I was quite a shy kid.</i>

01:06:54.960 --> 01:06:57.254
<i>I could relate
to that kind of feeling</i>

01:06:57.338 --> 01:07:00.799
of not quite knowing
what your place is.

01:07:00.883 --> 01:07:02.801
<i>Working hard is important,</i>

01:07:02.885 --> 01:07:04.470
but there's something
that matters even more.

01:07:04.553 --> 01:07:06.764
- Stupefy!
- Believing in yourself.

01:07:09.183 --> 01:07:12.227
<i>Everyone felt
more like they belonged</i>

01:07:12.311 --> 01:07:15.397
by witnessing these characters
that didn't belong.

01:07:18.651 --> 01:07:20.486
<i>Bonnie was,
kind of, when she arrived,</i>

01:07:20.569 --> 01:07:23.864
she was only 9, maybe.

01:07:23.948 --> 01:07:25.449
Mummy, have you seen
my jumper?

01:07:25.532 --> 01:07:27.785
Yes, dear, it was on the cat.

01:07:27.868 --> 01:07:29.244
Hello.

01:07:29.328 --> 01:07:32.373
I always found Ginny, Harry,
that relationship,

01:07:32.456 --> 01:07:35.250
how that kind of
slowly developed

01:07:35.334 --> 01:07:39.505
and entangling with it
the whole Weasley family

01:07:39.588 --> 01:07:42.883
<i>and Harry essentially
becoming a Weasley, himself.</i>

01:07:43.968 --> 01:07:45.511
It was something I never
really kind of expected,

01:07:45.594 --> 01:07:47.262
especially kind
of reading the books.

01:07:47.346 --> 01:07:49.014
<i>Bonnie was the youngest one.</i>

01:07:49.098 --> 01:07:51.600
So it was just a bit like,
"Oh, what? This is weird."

01:07:52.601 --> 01:07:54.061
Close your eyes.

01:07:54.144 --> 01:07:56.271
<i>And you know, there is
this kind of pressure.</i>

01:07:56.355 --> 01:08:00.025
You know, this is the loved
sort of hero of the story.

01:08:00.109 --> 01:08:02.194
So everyone on the set
has known you

01:08:02.277 --> 01:08:04.571
for about six or seven years,
and they've watched you grow up

01:08:04.655 --> 01:08:07.116
<i>and they're now gonna
just watch you kiss.</i>

01:08:07.199 --> 01:08:08.409
Cool. Yeah.

01:08:15.708 --> 01:08:18.294
<i>I mean, there's so many
amazing female roles</i>

01:08:18.377 --> 01:08:20.754
that Jo wrote, and I think
that's really important.

01:08:20.837 --> 01:08:26.343
I am so proud of who Bonnie
and Evanna and Katie are

01:08:26.426 --> 01:08:27.845
and who they've become.

01:08:27.928 --> 01:08:31.055
They've all become
these incredible activists.

01:08:31.140 --> 01:08:34.727
Every single one of those girls
was like a lovely,

01:08:34.810 --> 01:08:36.895
great human being.

01:08:41.984 --> 01:08:43.902
I tell you,
I've... I've missed your company.

01:08:43.986 --> 01:08:45.738
- Did you? Aw, thank you.
- That's for sure.

01:08:45.821 --> 01:08:47.406
Did you get anything?
'Cause I stole quite a lot.

01:08:47.488 --> 01:08:48.782
- Did you really?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:08:48.866 --> 01:08:50.451
I didn't.
I should have known that.

01:08:50.533 --> 01:08:52.077
- I should have told you.
- I'm quite reassured by that.

01:08:52.161 --> 01:08:55.247
'cause I was definitely
trying to steal my wand.

01:08:55.330 --> 01:08:56.707
And I worry that if I had,

01:08:56.790 --> 01:08:58.207
I probably would have
lost it by now somewhere.

01:08:58.292 --> 01:09:00.169
You know they don't work,
Tom.

01:09:00.252 --> 01:09:01.545
Well, I've been assured

01:09:01.627 --> 01:09:04.548
that in time,
with enough practice...

01:09:04.631 --> 01:09:06.508
- Practice it would work.
- Yes.

01:09:06.591 --> 01:09:08.469
But it's quite funny
looking back at it now,

01:09:08.551 --> 01:09:10.763
us doing these
incredibly elaborate moves

01:09:10.845 --> 01:09:12.348
and nothing happening.

01:09:12.430 --> 01:09:14.640
And nothing... except one time
it did happen with me.

01:09:14.725 --> 01:09:17.644
And they said, okay, this time
we are gonna blow up Hogwarts.

01:09:17.728 --> 01:09:19.772
Oh, yeah, you got to do it,
didn't you? Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:09:19.854 --> 01:09:21.939
And they said,
so we will take your cue.

01:09:22.024 --> 01:09:24.318
When you do your spell,
it will blow up.

01:09:26.236 --> 01:09:30.240
And I was actually
really surprised and scared

01:09:30.323 --> 01:09:32.618
by my own reaction,
'cause I thought, "Wow."

01:09:36.205 --> 01:09:38.122
<i>It was this horrible thrill
of power.</i>

01:09:38.207 --> 01:09:39.625
<i>Right.</i>

01:09:39.707 --> 01:09:41.835
And, like, I've had
that amount... just pointing

01:09:41.919 --> 01:09:43.962
my wand there
and then it blew up.

01:09:44.046 --> 01:09:45.798
Yeah, it's a lot
more satisfying than,

01:09:45.881 --> 01:09:47.674
you know,
making a feather levitate.

01:09:47.758 --> 01:09:50.469
Yeah.

01:09:51.428 --> 01:09:52.805
<i>So what was Draco doing</i>

01:09:52.888 --> 01:09:54.348
<i>with that
weird-looking cabinet,</i>

01:09:54.431 --> 01:09:56.975
and who were all those people?
Don't you see?

01:09:57.059 --> 01:09:59.394
It was a ceremony,
an initiation.

01:09:59.478 --> 01:10:00.687
Stop it, Harry.

01:10:00.771 --> 01:10:01.980
I know where
you're going with this.

01:10:02.064 --> 01:10:04.358
It happened.
He's one of them.

01:10:04.441 --> 01:10:05.526
One of what?

01:10:06.610 --> 01:10:07.861
Harry is under the impression

01:10:07.945 --> 01:10:10.239
Draco Malfoy is now
a Death Eater.

01:10:14.243 --> 01:10:16.036
<i>The child who hasn't
received affection,</i>

01:10:16.120 --> 01:10:19.123
<i>the enabling love
of the parent or the adult</i>

01:10:19.206 --> 01:10:22.334
can develop this anger
and hatred at the world

01:10:22.417 --> 01:10:23.877
<i>and goes to the dark side.</i>

01:10:23.961 --> 01:10:26.088
You dare to talk to me
like that in my own house?

01:10:26.171 --> 01:10:27.381
Lucius.

01:10:27.464 --> 01:10:29.675
So much of what
Draco's journey is,

01:10:29.758 --> 01:10:31.385
is to do with
whether he is or isn't

01:10:31.468 --> 01:10:32.886
trying to please his father.

01:10:32.970 --> 01:10:34.847
<i>In the sixth film,
they make him do</i>

01:10:34.930 --> 01:10:37.266
<i>the worst thing ever, or to
attempt the worst thing ever,</i>

01:10:37.349 --> 01:10:40.519
<i>of killing Dumbledore, and
obviously we see him crumble.</i>

01:10:40.602 --> 01:10:44.481
Draco, years ago,
I knew a boy

01:10:44.565 --> 01:10:47.568
who made all the wrong choices.

01:10:48.819 --> 01:10:51.697
- Please let me help you.
- I don't want your help.

01:10:52.698 --> 01:10:54.700
Don't you understand?

01:10:54.783 --> 01:10:56.451
I have to do this.

01:10:57.536 --> 01:10:59.621
I have to kill you.

01:10:59.705 --> 01:11:01.248
Or he's gonna kill me.

01:11:01.331 --> 01:11:02.833
<i>With Tom, what was great
with "Half-Blood Prince"</i>

01:11:02.916 --> 01:11:05.544
was you suddenly
took this bad guy

01:11:05.627 --> 01:11:07.087
<i>who, in the previous films,</i>

01:11:07.171 --> 01:11:10.048
<i>had always been
somewhat two dimensional.</i>

01:11:10.132 --> 01:11:12.718
And then we were able
to give him the opportunity

01:11:12.801 --> 01:11:17.139
to explore a far more complex
and interesting journey.

01:11:17.222 --> 01:11:19.308
<i>And I sat down with him
and I said, "Tom, look,</i>

01:11:19.391 --> 01:11:21.977
this is your opportunity
to really shine."

01:11:22.060 --> 01:11:25.230
I remember David Yates saying
if we can get

01:11:25.314 --> 01:11:28.692
just 1% of empathy
or sympathy for him,

01:11:28.775 --> 01:11:30.569
<i>then we'll have done our job.</i>

01:11:30.652 --> 01:11:32.029
Do it.

01:11:32.988 --> 01:11:34.531
<i>To my mind,
Draco is the hero.</i>

01:11:34.615 --> 01:11:36.033
<i>Harry's always gonna
do the right thing.</i>

01:11:36.116 --> 01:11:37.534
Harry's always gonna make
the right choice.

01:11:37.618 --> 01:11:39.495
There's never really
any dilemma for him.

01:11:39.578 --> 01:11:42.623
<i>Draco breaks the chains
of this terrible family</i>

01:11:42.706 --> 01:11:45.083
<i>in his responsibility
and what he's expected to do.</i>

01:11:45.167 --> 01:11:49.421
And to watch Tom create
that struggle on-screen

01:11:49.504 --> 01:11:51.590
<i>and really manifest
all that nuance,</i>

01:11:51.673 --> 01:11:52.758
all that complication,

01:11:52.841 --> 01:11:54.509
all that great
ethical minefield

01:11:54.593 --> 01:11:58.388
that he tiptoes through
was... it was just so impressive.

01:11:58.472 --> 01:11:59.806
No.

01:12:11.693 --> 01:12:13.278
Severus.

01:12:22.162 --> 01:12:23.747
Please.

01:12:24.665 --> 01:12:26.500
<i>Avada Kedavra!</i>

01:12:37.052 --> 01:12:38.804
It's obviously amazing
to be back,

01:12:38.887 --> 01:12:41.807
but it's like it's so...

01:12:41.890 --> 01:12:44.810
I guess, like,
shocking that so many people

01:12:44.893 --> 01:12:47.562
that we both thought
would be around for much longer

01:12:47.646 --> 01:12:49.648
than they have been,

01:12:49.731 --> 01:12:54.403
like Helen and Alan
and Richard and...

01:12:54.486 --> 01:12:57.322
Yeah, they're like fam...
like family,

01:12:57.406 --> 01:12:59.157
you can grieve in the same way.

01:12:59.241 --> 01:13:02.327
- Yeah.
- Just too soon.

01:13:02.411 --> 01:13:03.954
Yeah.

01:13:13.964 --> 01:13:17.009
<i>Do not pity the dead, Harry.</i>

01:13:17.092 --> 01:13:19.511
<i>Pity the living,</i>

01:13:19.594 --> 01:13:23.765
<i>and above all, all those
who live without love.</i>

01:13:29.104 --> 01:13:32.774
It does not do
to dwell on dreams, Harry,

01:13:32.858 --> 01:13:35.110
and forget to live.

01:13:38.113 --> 01:13:43.368
Richard Harris was
such a special, warm person.

01:13:44.661 --> 01:13:46.496
<i>He was so twinkly.</i>

01:13:48.665 --> 01:13:50.167
Well, Richard was classic.

01:13:50.250 --> 01:13:52.878
Probably one of
the funniest men I've ever met.

01:13:52.961 --> 01:13:54.880
He was this devilish
11-year-old

01:13:54.963 --> 01:13:57.966
trapped in
a 70-plus-year-old man's body.

01:13:58.050 --> 01:14:00.302
Will you give us
another twirl, ace?

01:14:02.054 --> 01:14:03.597
He just had
that glint in his eye,

01:14:03.680 --> 01:14:06.016
which made him the perfect
Dumbledore, by the way.

01:14:06.099 --> 01:14:08.143
Hmm, alas.

01:14:09.770 --> 01:14:11.188
Ear wax.

01:14:11.271 --> 01:14:15.984
Richard Griffiths was just
delicious as Mr. Dursley.

01:14:16.068 --> 01:14:19.071
There's no such thing
as magic.

01:14:20.113 --> 01:14:23.408
<i>He embraced his wickedness</i>

01:14:23.492 --> 01:14:25.577
with such verve and passion.

01:14:25.660 --> 01:14:27.954
<i>His passing was the one
that has affected me most</i>

01:14:28.038 --> 01:14:29.581
<i>because he was generous
with knowledge.</i>

01:14:29.664 --> 01:14:31.583
Just, like, wanted to share
everything with you.

01:14:38.256 --> 01:14:42.427
I wondered when I'd be
seeing you, Mr. Potter.

01:14:43.428 --> 01:14:46.264
I feel really lucky
to have some, you know,

01:14:46.348 --> 01:14:47.933
some little bit of touch

01:14:48.016 --> 01:14:50.227
<i>with the amount of just
amazing people that passed.</i>

01:14:51.603 --> 01:14:54.106
You know, I'll be very,
very old one day saying, like,

01:14:54.189 --> 01:14:56.775
"I knew that absolute legend."

01:14:56.858 --> 01:14:58.735
I... I know
I ought not be here.

01:15:00.362 --> 01:15:03.573
The Dark Lord himself
forbade me to speak of this.

01:15:03.657 --> 01:15:05.367
<i>Helen McCrory played
my wife.</i>

01:15:05.450 --> 01:15:07.327
I said, "I think I just met

01:15:07.411 --> 01:15:09.788
the best actress
I've ever seen in my life."

01:15:10.831 --> 01:15:11.957
Come.

01:15:12.040 --> 01:15:13.959
I feel lucky to have worked
with her

01:15:14.042 --> 01:15:16.128
and shared just so much,

01:15:16.211 --> 01:15:18.922
<i>frankly, adolescent laughter
with her on the set.</i>

01:15:20.882 --> 01:15:22.592
<i>She had taught me a lot.</i>

01:15:23.760 --> 01:15:25.804
See, I can't even say it.

01:15:30.183 --> 01:15:31.685
She had this ability, yeah,

01:15:31.768 --> 01:15:36.523
just to sort of to show
such empathy in her eyes.

01:15:37.232 --> 01:15:39.484
<i>And it was a... it was
a real treat to work with her.</i>

01:15:44.739 --> 01:15:46.158
I can teach you

01:15:46.241 --> 01:15:50.537
how to bewitch the mind
and ensnare the senses.

01:15:50.620 --> 01:15:53.748
Alan Rickman never talked
to me like I was a child.

01:15:53.832 --> 01:15:57.210
He always took
my thoughts and opinions

01:15:57.294 --> 01:16:01.923
very seriously, which I was
always very touched by.

01:16:02.007 --> 01:16:05.844
Alan was a very dear friend,
and we had that final scene.

01:16:05.927 --> 01:16:07.637
His final scene.

01:16:08.513 --> 01:16:12.017
It answers to you

01:16:12.100 --> 01:16:14.519
and you only.

01:16:15.353 --> 01:16:16.772
Does it?

01:16:16.855 --> 01:16:19.107
<i>I was a little intimidated
by him.</i>

01:16:19.191 --> 01:16:22.444
His precision,
his expert delivery of lines.

01:16:22.527 --> 01:16:24.738
<i>And we were sort of went
toe to toe in a funny way,</i>

01:16:24.821 --> 01:16:26.531
<i>you know, Snape and Voldemort.</i>

01:16:26.615 --> 01:16:28.074
<i>Two actors can relish</i>

01:16:28.158 --> 01:16:29.826
<i>metaphorically fencing
with each other.</i>

01:16:29.910 --> 01:16:33.121
Alan was a magician
in that way as an actor.

01:16:38.126 --> 01:16:40.587
<i>The ones that love us
never really leave us.</i>

01:16:41.963 --> 01:16:43.715
And you can always find them.

01:16:46.384 --> 01:16:47.552
In here.

01:17:23.505 --> 01:17:25.006
<i>Remember this.</i>

01:17:26.258 --> 01:17:28.176
You're not alone.

01:17:32.180 --> 01:17:33.807
The Elder Wand.

01:17:36.351 --> 01:17:38.979
<i>The most powerful wand
ever made.</i>

01:17:39.062 --> 01:17:41.439
The Resurrection Stone.

01:17:45.986 --> 01:17:48.947
The Cloak of Invisibility.

01:17:50.198 --> 01:17:52.450
Together they make
the Deathly Hallows.

01:17:52.534 --> 01:17:56.329
Together they make
one Master of Death.

01:17:57.414 --> 01:17:59.416
The boy who lived.

01:18:02.043 --> 01:18:03.169
Harry!

01:18:09.092 --> 01:18:10.427
<i>Come to die.</i>

01:18:10.510 --> 01:18:11.428
No!

01:18:14.180 --> 01:18:16.016
<i>Avada Kedavra!</i>

01:18:28.653 --> 01:18:31.990
<i>The measures they had taken
to protect their families</i>

01:18:32.073 --> 01:18:35.410
<i>made him realize more than
anything else could have done</i>

01:18:35.493 --> 01:18:38.163
<i>that they really were
going to come with him</i>

01:18:38.246 --> 01:18:42.167
<i>and that they knew exactly
how dangerous that would be.</i>

01:18:42.250 --> 01:18:44.961
<i>He wanted to tell them
what that meant to him,</i>

01:18:45.045 --> 01:18:49.215
<i>but he simply could not find
words important enough.</i>

01:18:58.600 --> 01:19:00.185
It's both really cool.

01:19:00.268 --> 01:19:03.438
It's really... and it's weird,
like, walking around here

01:19:03.521 --> 01:19:06.858
and seeing the sets
that we were, like, kids on,

01:19:06.941 --> 01:19:08.735
who treated everything
with the amount of respect

01:19:08.818 --> 01:19:10.403
kids treat things when you're
just there and having fun.

01:19:10.487 --> 01:19:11.780
- Yeah.
- It's weird.

01:19:11.863 --> 01:19:13.073
I'm having, like,
weird, nostalgic moments.

01:19:13.156 --> 01:19:14.366
Remember my hamster?

01:19:14.449 --> 01:19:15.408
Does anybody
remember my hamster?

01:19:15.492 --> 01:19:16.868
- Yes.
- Millie.

01:19:16.951 --> 01:19:18.203
Yeah. I didn't remember
the hamster's name.

01:19:18.286 --> 01:19:19.579
- I'm sorry.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:19:19.663 --> 01:19:20.872
That's okay.
Rest in peace, Millie.

01:19:20.955 --> 01:19:22.415
I remember you having
a hamster

01:19:22.499 --> 01:19:24.084
and being vaguely jealous
that you had an animal

01:19:24.167 --> 01:19:26.461
- that was on set with you.
- They made a coffin for it.

01:19:26.544 --> 01:19:27.879
- The carpentry department.
- They did, yeah.

01:19:27.962 --> 01:19:30.090
When Millie died,
the set designers built

01:19:30.173 --> 01:19:33.802
Millie her own
custom-made wooden coffin

01:19:33.885 --> 01:19:35.470
that had velvet
on the inside of it.

01:19:35.553 --> 01:19:36.721
- It was beautiful.
- Whoa!

01:19:36.805 --> 01:19:38.890
And... and it had
her name engraved

01:19:38.973 --> 01:19:41.267
because I was, I mean,
I was beside myself.

01:19:41.351 --> 01:19:42.560
Did we do, like, a service?

01:19:42.644 --> 01:19:44.229
I feel like we said
a few words.

01:19:44.312 --> 01:19:47.607
I kept wanting to pick up
dead Millie, and, like,

01:19:47.691 --> 01:19:49.776
stroke and touch dead Millie.

01:19:49.859 --> 01:19:51.486
And he was like, "Emma,

01:19:51.569 --> 01:19:54.739
Millie's got to, like,
stay in the coffin now."

01:19:54.823 --> 01:19:57.117
I have forgotten
so much of this.

01:19:57.200 --> 01:20:00.078
It doesn't feel like
much time has passed.

01:20:00.161 --> 01:20:01.663
I know.

01:20:01.746 --> 01:20:03.039
We all still look better
than we do in the epilogue.

01:20:03.123 --> 01:20:04.749
- Yes.
- I was gonna say.

01:20:04.833 --> 01:20:06.167
Which is great. Like,
we've made it in before that.

01:20:08.712 --> 01:20:10.755
- Bag?
- Yeah.

01:20:10.839 --> 01:20:12.048
Jumper?

01:20:12.132 --> 01:20:15.385
I was all forehead
and a fat suit.

01:20:15.468 --> 01:20:17.554
- Yeah, I was very, I was...
- I think I kind of...

01:20:17.637 --> 01:20:18.972
Yeah, you went for it.

01:20:19.055 --> 01:20:20.390
You were like,
"Give me the full, give me..."

01:20:20.473 --> 01:20:21.474
I did, yeah.
Give me everything.

01:20:21.558 --> 01:20:22.684
Yeah, you went all in.

01:20:22.767 --> 01:20:25.186
- Yeah.
- I was so proud of you.

01:20:27.188 --> 01:20:29.190
<i>No one else can really quite
understand</i>

01:20:29.274 --> 01:20:31.484
<i>what we experienced;
it's a very unique thing.</i>

01:20:31.568 --> 01:20:34.821
Think David Yates used
to describe us as astronauts

01:20:34.904 --> 01:20:38.825
'cause no one else has really
experienced this in this scale.

01:20:38.908 --> 01:20:41.578
And we'll be kind of
forever bonded by that.

01:20:46.499 --> 01:20:47.917
<i>Some of
the sweetest memories I have</i>

01:20:48.001 --> 01:20:49.544
from the three of us
is just each of us

01:20:49.627 --> 01:20:52.046
knowing we sort of needed
to take care of each other

01:20:52.130 --> 01:20:53.548
in just small ways.

01:20:53.631 --> 01:20:55.467
<i>Just in terms of, like,
it's really cold.</i>

01:20:55.550 --> 01:20:58.803
Like we're all gonna...
we're all gonna stand together

01:20:58.887 --> 01:21:00.430
or I'm knackered.

01:21:00.513 --> 01:21:03.391
Are you okay, Dan,
if I, like, fall asleep on you,

01:21:03.475 --> 01:21:07.145
like, in between this take,
'cause I'm so tired or...

01:21:07.228 --> 01:21:09.481
I think we have all
fallen asleep in various

01:21:09.564 --> 01:21:10.899
like on... on each other

01:21:10.982 --> 01:21:12.817
in, like, some of
the most grand cathedrals

01:21:12.901 --> 01:21:15.570
and things in the UK.

01:21:15.653 --> 01:21:17.322
<i>The level of trust I had</i>

01:21:17.405 --> 01:21:20.492
and that we did build
over those 10 years was like,

01:21:20.575 --> 01:21:22.160
if we were doing a stunt,

01:21:22.243 --> 01:21:24.996
<i>I trusted that
one of you would catch me.</i>

01:21:25.079 --> 01:21:26.790
<i>I feel like that kind of
trust and reliance</i>

01:21:26.873 --> 01:21:28.917
and that takes, you know,

01:21:29.000 --> 01:21:30.502
there's very few
work environments

01:21:30.585 --> 01:21:32.003
where you get that much time
to build that up.

01:21:32.086 --> 01:21:33.755
And it was like nonverbal.
Like it was,

01:21:33.838 --> 01:21:35.590
it was like the three of us
could communicate

01:21:35.673 --> 01:21:37.884
without even having
to say anything.

01:21:37.967 --> 01:21:39.844
We just knew
what needed to be done.

01:21:39.928 --> 01:21:43.264
We were each very strong
for each other.

01:21:44.516 --> 01:21:46.100
Need to change.

01:21:52.440 --> 01:21:53.691
How, Hermione?

01:21:53.775 --> 01:21:55.735
Undetectable extension charm.

01:21:57.028 --> 01:21:58.404
You're amazing, you are.

01:21:59.489 --> 01:22:01.449
Always the tone of surprise.

01:22:01.533 --> 01:22:03.993
<i>These films had
a very different feel.</i>

01:22:04.077 --> 01:22:05.578
<i>We were away from Hogwarts.</i>

01:22:05.662 --> 01:22:08.748
A lot of the time
camping out different places.

01:22:08.832 --> 01:22:10.500
<i>The tone was a lot darker.</i>

01:22:10.583 --> 01:22:12.210
<i>It felt like a different film.</i>

01:22:12.293 --> 01:22:14.295
Dumbledore sends you off
to find all these Horcruxes,

01:22:14.379 --> 01:22:16.047
but it doesn't tell you
how to destroy them?

01:22:16.130 --> 01:22:17.757
It's very refreshing,
I think,

01:22:17.841 --> 01:22:21.261
'cause we all got to do
some a lot more serious stuff.

01:22:21.344 --> 01:22:22.929
<i>And it was a real opportunity</i>

01:22:23.012 --> 01:22:24.556
to go deeper with these
characters.

